WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
You're watching from StreamFlex app. 
Enjoy watching.

02:59.040 --> 03:01.713
JAKE: Do you ever feel like
nothing you do matters?

03:03.000 --> 03:04.433
You leave footprints
on the beach,

03:04.520 --> 03:05.839
and tomorrow they're gone.

03:07.080 --> 03:08.718
Like it's just today
over again.

03:11.240 --> 03:12.468
They say your teen years

03:12.560 --> 03:14.869
are for making friends
and having fun...

03:15.040 --> 03:17.429
which made me feel even worse.

03:17.600 --> 03:20.273
Hey, Amy. It's Jake.

03:20.440 --> 03:21.998
I'm in your math class.

03:22.960 --> 03:24.400
Hey, don't forget
your adult diapers.

03:24.480 --> 03:25.480
Yeah, right.

03:26.440 --> 03:27.759
(GASPS AND LAUGHS)

03:28.640 --> 03:29.959
(LAUGHTER)

03:33.000 --> 03:35.798
Jake. Phone for you.

03:36.360 --> 03:38.874
But that day,
everything changed.

03:42.320 --> 03:43.639
Thanks for
the ride, Shelley.

03:44.680 --> 03:46.989
So, how come you have to go
deal with your grandpa?

03:47.200 --> 03:49.555
My dad couldn't
get out of work.

03:49.720 --> 03:51.790
I didn't think he worked.

03:56.040 --> 03:59.112
I'm just gonna call Grandpa.

03:59.840 --> 04:01.353
(PHONE RINGING)

04:01.720 --> 04:03.039
ABE: Hello, this is Abe.

04:03.200 --> 04:04.679
JAKE: (ON PHONE)
Hey, it's Jake.

04:04.840 --> 04:08.071
No! Don't come here.
Listen to me.

04:08.240 --> 04:09.912
It's not safe.

04:10.080 --> 04:11.115
Stay away.

04:11.280 --> 04:13.635
Grandpa, did you take
your pills today?

04:13.800 --> 04:17.509
The key to my gun cabinet,
it was in the drawer.

04:17.680 --> 04:18.999
And now it's gone.

04:19.720 --> 04:22.359
Yeah, Dad took it,
all right?

04:22.520 --> 04:25.637
For safekeeping. It's okay.

04:26.360 --> 04:28.376
Your father wants I should
fight them without a gun?

04:28.400 --> 04:29.469
(DISCONNECTS CALL)

04:34.120 --> 04:35.599
God bless him.

04:36.200 --> 04:38.156
What's his deal,
Alzheimer's?

04:38.640 --> 04:39.993
Dementia.

04:55.320 --> 04:56.320
(TIRES SCREECHING)

05:00.240 --> 05:02.959
That guy gave me
the heebie-jeebies.

05:12.680 --> 05:14.591
Holler if you need me.

05:21.320 --> 05:22.469
(KNOCKING LOUDLY)

05:22.680 --> 05:23.908
Grandpa?

05:30.040 --> 05:31.075
(GASPS)

05:38.040 --> 05:40.110
(PANTING)

05:48.360 --> 05:49.360
(SHOUTS) Shelley!

05:55.280 --> 05:56.280
What's goin' on?

05:56.720 --> 05:57.869
Someone broke in.

05:58.200 --> 06:00.589
I've got a.38 in my car.
You wait there.

06:03.400 --> 06:05.277
(RUSTLING)

06:14.160 --> 06:16.196
(WIND WHOOSHING)

06:38.360 --> 06:39.395
(DEEP CREAKING)

06:39.480 --> 06:40.595
(GASPS)

06:49.640 --> 06:50.709
Grandpa!

07:03.560 --> 07:05.296
FEMALE DISPATCHER:
911. What's your emergency?

07:05.320 --> 07:07.515
911? Yeah,
I need the paramedics.

07:07.680 --> 07:09.989
It's at 2040 Palm Circle.
My grandpa...

07:11.240 --> 07:12.376
DISPATCHER:
Sir, what's your emergency?

07:12.400 --> 07:13.400
Grandpa.

07:13.480 --> 07:15.471
You have to get away
from here.

07:15.640 --> 07:16.920
DISPATCHER:
Sir, can you hear me?

07:16.960 --> 07:18.791
Please. Listen.
(STAMMERS)

07:19.000 --> 07:20.672
Go to the island.

07:20.840 --> 07:22.637
Sir, paramedics
are on their way.

07:22.800 --> 07:24.916
Find Emerson.

07:26.160 --> 07:27.832
The postcard.

07:28.000 --> 07:29.513
Go to the loop.

07:29.680 --> 07:32.399
September 3rd, 1943.

07:32.960 --> 07:34.109
It's okay.

07:34.280 --> 07:36.191
Just don't move. There's
an ambulance coming.

07:36.360 --> 07:39.272
I know you think I'm crazy.

07:39.640 --> 07:42.473
But the bird
will explain everything.

07:43.520 --> 07:46.717
Will you do this, Tygrysku?
Promise me?

07:46.880 --> 07:48.313
I promise, yes.

07:48.480 --> 07:50.914
I thought I could protect you.

07:53.320 --> 07:57.154
I should have told you
years ago.

07:57.600 --> 07:59.636
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

08:03.960 --> 08:06.315
Grandpa. Tell me what?

08:06.680 --> 08:07.908
Grandpa!

08:12.200 --> 08:13.713
(INDISTINCT BELLOWING)
(RUSTLING)

08:13.800 --> 08:14.915
(GASPS)

08:15.680 --> 08:17.477
(RUSTLING CONTINUES)

08:28.520 --> 08:30.078
Shelley, behind you!

08:30.160 --> 08:31.559
(GUNSHOTS)

08:44.400 --> 08:47.198
There was no one there.

08:48.160 --> 08:49.957
May I say, Jake...

08:50.120 --> 08:52.270
that considering this
was only a month ago...

08:52.440 --> 08:54.908
I think you're doing
exceptionally well.

08:55.400 --> 08:57.789
Apart from being crazy?

08:58.680 --> 09:02.229
Having nightmares and anxiety
doesn't make you crazy.

09:02.400 --> 09:05.915
What about seeing things
which aren't there?

09:06.080 --> 09:07.176
Actually,
in traumatic situations,

09:07.200 --> 09:08.428
it's not at all uncommon.

09:08.600 --> 09:12.195
Your subconscious mind drew
an image from a movie or...

09:12.400 --> 09:13.833
It was a story.

09:15.120 --> 09:17.588
My grandpa told me stories
when I was a kid...

09:17.760 --> 09:20.479
about monsters that
he fought in the war.

09:20.640 --> 09:21.640
So there you go.

09:21.800 --> 09:23.518
He was
brutally attacked...

09:23.680 --> 09:26.990
and in your head, the man who
did it was inhuman, a monster.

09:27.160 --> 09:29.435
It wasn't a man, though.

09:29.960 --> 09:31.916
The cops said that dogs

09:32.000 --> 09:34.195
scratched up
the screen door...

09:34.360 --> 09:37.318
and he chased them off
into the woods.

09:37.480 --> 09:39.675
And the coroner said
he had a heart attack.

09:40.240 --> 09:41.832
And the cops said...

09:43.040 --> 09:44.109
(SNIFFLES)

09:44.280 --> 09:46.874
that dogs go
for the soft parts.

09:47.840 --> 09:49.558
They DNA tested the fork...

09:49.720 --> 09:52.553
and it had animal DNA.

09:52.760 --> 09:54.990
So, that's case closed.

09:56.120 --> 09:58.839
He sounds like
an extraordinary gentleman.

09:59.320 --> 10:01.276
Were you very close?

10:01.920 --> 10:02.920
ABE: Puerto Rico.

10:04.280 --> 10:05.280
Here.

10:05.560 --> 10:08.438
There's a lake where the
water glows in the dark.

10:08.760 --> 10:10.512
And a secret tunnel.

10:10.680 --> 10:12.989
That's where I hid
from the monsters.

10:13.480 --> 10:15.357
JAKE: He used to
babysit me a lot.

10:15.800 --> 10:17.791
When I was with him,
I felt special.

10:17.920 --> 10:19.273
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

10:19.480 --> 10:21.118
My duck was dry again.

10:22.440 --> 10:25.671
Abe. It's, like, 11:00.
What is he doing up?

10:27.000 --> 10:28.638
I'm gonna
be an explorer.

10:28.720 --> 10:31.632
Grandpa's helping me
plan my first voyage.

10:31.800 --> 10:33.950
Everything's already
been discovered, buddy.

10:35.680 --> 10:37.256
MAN: (ON TV)
They terrorize each other...

10:37.280 --> 10:39.953
before wreaking havoc
on the rest of the island.

10:40.160 --> 10:41.400
Pay no attention
to your father.

10:41.440 --> 10:42.509
He knows bubkes.

10:42.680 --> 10:46.036
Come, Tygrysku. Off to bed.

10:48.040 --> 10:49.553
MAN: (ON TV)
And they're not choosy.

10:49.640 --> 10:51.358
These talons
come in squadrons.

10:52.120 --> 10:54.714
MAN: (ON TV) Touchdown,
Florida! What a drive.

10:55.280 --> 10:56.918
Can you tell me a story?

10:57.000 --> 10:58.000
The usual?

10:58.080 --> 10:59.080
Mmm-hmm.

10:59.560 --> 11:02.791
Okay. Once upon a time...

11:02.960 --> 11:04.234
there was a little boy...

11:04.400 --> 11:05.799
With the pictures.

11:06.440 --> 11:07.589
Pictures.

11:15.720 --> 11:17.039
Once upon a time...

11:17.200 --> 11:19.839
there was a little boy
called Abe.

11:20.000 --> 11:21.319
That was you.

11:21.760 --> 11:22.760
That was me.

11:22.920 --> 11:26.151
And he lived in a
lovely children's home

11:26.240 --> 11:27.878
on a little island
near Wales...

11:28.080 --> 11:30.230
where the sun
shone every day.

11:31.320 --> 11:34.198
The headmistress,
Miss Peregrine...

11:34.360 --> 11:36.237
was very clever.

11:36.400 --> 11:38.868
And she smoked a pipe.

11:39.040 --> 11:40.189
She could turn into a bird.

11:40.360 --> 11:41.509
Mmm-hmm.

11:41.800 --> 11:45.679
It was a home
for special children...

11:45.840 --> 11:49.071
like Bronwyn and Victor.

11:50.160 --> 11:52.799
They were both as strong
as 10 men.

11:53.600 --> 11:54.749
And Hugh...

11:54.920 --> 11:58.310
Hugh had bees
living inside him.

11:59.640 --> 12:00.640
JAKE: Where's Emma?

12:00.800 --> 12:02.552
She could float.

12:03.320 --> 12:06.630
She was lighter than air.

12:06.800 --> 12:10.031
She had to wear special
shoes made of lead

12:10.120 --> 12:11.951
to keep her
from floating away.

12:12.800 --> 12:14.711
Where is she now?

12:14.920 --> 12:17.388
She's still on the island,
I believe.

12:18.240 --> 12:20.470
My mama and papa
sent me there...

12:20.640 --> 12:22.915
to live with
the special children.

12:23.080 --> 12:26.436
And now, Tygrysku,
time for sleep.

12:26.640 --> 12:28.437
JAKE: He used to
call me Tygrysku.

12:28.640 --> 12:30.517
It's Polish
for "little tiger."

12:31.000 --> 12:33.195
He couldn't have picked
a less appropriate nickname.

12:33.360 --> 12:34.759
I was always a chicken.

12:34.920 --> 12:37.593
Why did your mom and dad
send you away?

12:38.800 --> 12:42.349
Well, where we lived
in Poland, it wasn't safe.

12:43.040 --> 12:44.314
There were monsters.

12:44.480 --> 12:46.755
What kind of monsters?

12:46.920 --> 12:50.708
Huge ones,
with long arms...

12:50.880 --> 12:52.791
and no eyes...

12:53.000 --> 12:55.560
and tentacles like this.

12:55.960 --> 12:57.678
(EVIL LAUGH)

12:58.320 --> 13:00.515
The dumb thing was...

13:00.680 --> 13:02.830
for years, I actually
believed his stories.

13:04.320 --> 13:06.595
And this is Millard.
He's invisible.

13:07.000 --> 13:08.797
(LAUGHTER)

13:14.120 --> 13:16.873
My teacher says
they were trick photos.

13:17.640 --> 13:19.153
And did you believe her?

13:19.960 --> 13:21.313
Dad says you probably
found them

13:21.400 --> 13:22.674
at a junk store someplace...

13:22.840 --> 13:25.229
when you went traveling.

13:25.400 --> 13:27.868
I would never lie
to you, Tygrysku.

13:28.040 --> 13:33.478
But you did, about the
home, the monsters.

13:34.680 --> 13:36.113
Dad told me.

13:36.640 --> 13:38.596
Your father knows very well

13:38.680 --> 13:40.875
I went to live
in the children's home.

13:41.760 --> 13:44.991
He said there really were
monsters in Poland...

13:45.280 --> 13:48.272
just not the kind
with tentacles.

13:48.960 --> 13:52.157
He said you got sent to Wales
'cause there were bad people.

13:52.720 --> 13:56.599
People who wanted to kill
anyone who was different.

13:57.600 --> 13:59.716
I don't wanna talk
about this anymore.

13:59.880 --> 14:02.678
He said the children
were special...

14:04.040 --> 14:06.600
but not the way you said.

14:21.360 --> 14:22.918
(SQUIRMING)

14:23.400 --> 14:25.550
(GASPS AND PANTS)

14:26.560 --> 14:28.357
FRANK: I'm just saying,
tomorrow was

14:28.440 --> 14:30.158
supposed to be a writing day.

14:30.320 --> 14:32.993
JAKE'S MOM: Five years and
counting on that damn book.

14:33.160 --> 14:35.136
And taking one day to be with
your son on his birthday...

14:35.160 --> 14:36.354
is gonna be a big difference?

14:36.560 --> 14:37.560
FRANK: Fine.

14:45.200 --> 14:46.269
You find something good?

14:48.400 --> 14:51.153
Oh, look at that.
That's awesome.

14:51.760 --> 14:53.352
You should take that.

14:53.520 --> 14:55.397
Come on, buddy,
let's roll.

14:56.720 --> 14:58.836
How are you so okay?

15:00.200 --> 15:02.873
Jakey, you were a lot closer
to him than I ever was.

15:03.040 --> 15:04.871
He was
a wonderful grandpa...

15:05.040 --> 15:06.871
but not such a great dad.

15:09.200 --> 15:10.428
Never seemed
to pick a job...

15:10.600 --> 15:11.919
that didn't involve
late nights

15:12.000 --> 15:13.672
or long trips away, though.

15:14.160 --> 15:16.310
Me and Aunt Susie
always kind of thought

15:16.400 --> 15:19.233
he was, maybe,
cheating on our mom.

15:21.560 --> 15:23.680
I'm sorry, buddy. I know how
much you worshiped him...

15:23.720 --> 15:25.472
but there it is.

15:34.320 --> 15:35.799
ALL: Surprise!
(APPLAUSE)

15:35.960 --> 15:37.109
Happy birthday, Cousin Jake!

15:37.840 --> 15:39.016
J-dog, it's great
you're coming

15:39.040 --> 15:40.080
to spend a summer with us.

15:40.160 --> 15:41.434
Wait till you see
the new boat.

15:41.840 --> 15:43.360
Can't wait.
(MUSIC PLAYING ON SPEAKERS)

15:52.080 --> 15:53.115
(KNOCKS ON DOOR)

15:53.200 --> 15:54.792
It's Aunt Susie.

15:55.320 --> 15:57.675
Thought you might
wanna open this one.

15:57.840 --> 15:59.990
It's from your grandpa.

16:01.040 --> 16:02.314
Found it while
I was packing up.

16:02.520 --> 16:05.080
I figured he meant to
give it to you someday.

16:07.320 --> 16:08.469
Thanks.

16:08.560 --> 16:09.913
(CHUCKLES)

16:26.720 --> 16:30.633
ABE: To Jake, and the worlds
he has yet to discover.

16:42.080 --> 16:43.638
MISS PEREGRINE:
My dearest Abe...

16:43.800 --> 16:45.870
I hope this card
finds you well.

16:46.040 --> 16:49.077
The children and I yearn
to hear your news.

16:49.240 --> 16:51.595
I do hope you will
visit us again soon.

16:51.760 --> 16:53.557
We should so love to see you.

16:53.720 --> 16:55.073
With admiration...

16:55.280 --> 16:56.429
Alma Peregrine.

16:56.800 --> 16:58.916
H mm. Only two years ago.

16:59.120 --> 17:02.078
I suppose it's possible
she could still be alive.

17:02.640 --> 17:03.789
Right.

17:04.480 --> 17:06.516
I could meet her.

17:06.680 --> 17:08.113
Maybe even find out
what it was

17:08.200 --> 17:09.598
Grandpa wanted me to know.

17:09.760 --> 17:11.079
But what if
she's dead?

17:11.240 --> 17:12.240
Dr. Golan...

17:12.400 --> 17:13.594
we are very concerned

17:13.720 --> 17:15.472
with Jake's state of mind
right now.

17:15.680 --> 17:17.016
There's no way I'm putting
my life on hold

17:17.040 --> 17:18.108
to take you to Wales.

17:19.400 --> 17:20.913
Dad could take me.

17:21.079 --> 17:23.674
And he can look at birds...

17:23.839 --> 17:24.989
and work on his book.

17:25.440 --> 17:27.670
It means you get a break.

17:27.839 --> 17:29.193
As Dr. Golan said...

17:29.400 --> 17:31.595
maybe I can move on.

17:32.480 --> 17:33.708
Like, closure.

17:34.720 --> 17:37.393
Having an opportunity
to see this children's home...

17:37.560 --> 17:39.676
and separate fantasy
from reality...

17:40.280 --> 17:41.633
may be helpful.

17:41.800 --> 17:43.153
And at the very least...

17:43.320 --> 17:45.880
a trip like this provides
a chance to...

17:46.720 --> 17:48.199
say goodbye.

17:54.600 --> 17:57.114
JAKE: "Cairnholm.
Population of 92.

17:57.680 --> 17:59.557
"Best known
for its proximity...

17:59.760 --> 18:02.718
"to the final resting place
of the cruise liner Augusta...

18:02.880 --> 18:05.235
"which sank in 1915.

18:05.920 --> 18:07.717
"There is just one hotel..."

18:08.360 --> 18:09.429
That's us.

18:09.600 --> 18:11.477
Yeah. I hope there's bourbon.

18:11.560 --> 18:13.596
(SCREECHING)

18:13.960 --> 18:15.518
Oh, wow!

18:15.840 --> 18:17.398
Jake, check it out.

18:17.560 --> 18:19.676
That's a peregrine falcon.

18:19.840 --> 18:22.308
A peregrine,
like the headmistress?

18:23.080 --> 18:24.399
Sure.

18:24.560 --> 18:26.198
That's probably
where Grandpa came up

18:26.280 --> 18:28.032
with that whole turning
into a bird thing.

18:28.720 --> 18:31.678
Or maybe,
maybe that's really her!

18:31.880 --> 18:33.359
(SHOUTING)
Hey, Miss Peregrine.

18:33.520 --> 18:34.919
It's me, Jake.

18:35.080 --> 18:37.275
I'm Abe Portman's grandson.

18:37.440 --> 18:39.590
Please don't crap on us.

18:41.760 --> 18:44.069
Oh, my God.
Dad, I'm kidding.

19:11.360 --> 19:13.430
What the... Hello?

19:14.440 --> 19:15.589
Hello?

19:20.200 --> 19:21.792
Anybody home?

19:30.000 --> 19:31.558
(LAUGHS)

19:33.000 --> 19:34.000
Oh, hey.

19:34.160 --> 19:36.435
Any idea where I'd find
the manager of this place?

19:36.600 --> 19:38.636
That's me.
Sorry to keep you.

19:38.800 --> 19:40.677
Just helping Uncle Oggie
to the loo.

19:40.760 --> 19:41.988
Oh. Oh.

19:42.080 --> 19:43.832
KEV: I'm Kev.
There's room upstairs.

19:44.000 --> 19:45.000
Oh, great.

19:45.160 --> 19:46.195
I'll be back in a bit.

19:46.280 --> 19:47.315
Okay.

19:48.160 --> 19:50.151
FRANK: Kev's just getting
our suite ready.

19:51.160 --> 19:52.513
Um, while we're waiting...

19:52.680 --> 19:55.274
I thought maybe we could go
check out the beach.

19:55.440 --> 19:57.351
I thought we would go
to the children's home.

19:57.520 --> 19:59.795
Is the beach
where the birds nest?

19:59.960 --> 20:02.349
I thought we could just
check it out real quick.

20:02.520 --> 20:05.114
I could go to the home
by myself.

20:05.280 --> 20:08.909
Then, you can really
take your time and enjoy it.

20:09.080 --> 20:11.514
Come on, Jakey. You know
your mom would freak.

20:12.600 --> 20:14.909
What if we can find
someone to take me?

20:16.800 --> 20:17.869
FRANK: Hey, dudes.

20:18.600 --> 20:19.919
Dad. Don't.
Shh! I got this.

20:20.080 --> 20:21.720
I was just wondering
if any of you guys...

20:21.760 --> 20:23.216
might be interested
in taking my son here

20:23.240 --> 20:25.310
to the other side
of the island.

20:39.960 --> 20:41.473
So, what are your names?

20:41.640 --> 20:43.631
I'm Worm.
This is MC Dirty D.

20:43.840 --> 20:45.034
MC Dirty Bizniz.

20:45.200 --> 20:46.235
I thought you changed it.

20:46.320 --> 20:47.320
No.

20:47.400 --> 20:48.674
No, you did, remember?

20:48.840 --> 20:50.193
When Ruth said
"MC Dirty Bizniz"

20:50.280 --> 20:52.000
made it sound like
you cacked your trousers.

20:52.160 --> 20:54.037
Yeah, but she said
"Dirty D" sounded like

20:54.120 --> 20:55.189
a personal
hygiene problem.

20:55.360 --> 20:57.999
Wait. Are these, like,
nicknames, or...

20:58.160 --> 21:00.958
Stage names. We're the
sickest rappers in Wales.

21:01.120 --> 21:03.315
Go on, Worm. Show this
Yank how it's done.

21:03.480 --> 21:04.480
What? Now?

21:04.560 --> 21:05.595
(BEATBOXING)

21:05.680 --> 21:07.320
I like to get wrecked
down the Priest Hole

21:07.440 --> 21:09.240
Your dad's always here
'cause he's on the dole

21:09.360 --> 21:11.237
Our rhymes are tight
Yet I make it look easy

21:11.400 --> 21:13.470
Our beats are hot
like chicken jalfrezi

21:15.400 --> 21:17.516
Oh, yeah, no.
It's good.

21:18.240 --> 21:20.231
WORM: Should we take
the shortcut, D?

21:20.400 --> 21:22.516
We'll get there quicker.
Take it from me.

21:23.800 --> 21:24.994
What, down here?
Mm-hmm.

21:25.160 --> 21:26.160
Yeah.

21:32.320 --> 21:33.320
Go.

21:34.560 --> 21:36.073
(CHUCKLING)

21:40.680 --> 21:41.874
JAKE: This way?

21:43.920 --> 21:44.989
(SLOSHES)

21:45.520 --> 21:46.520
What the...

21:46.680 --> 21:47.908
(BOTH LAUGHING)

21:51.480 --> 21:54.153
Is this even the way
to the children's home?

21:54.320 --> 21:55.992
Right through those trees.

22:13.040 --> 22:14.598
(BREATH SHAKING)

22:22.400 --> 22:23.549
(OGGIE LAUGHS)

22:24.400 --> 22:27.437
No use crying
over a lost shoe, boy-o.

22:31.680 --> 22:34.114
The children's home.
What happened to it?

22:34.280 --> 22:37.989
A German air raid.
Bomb fell right on the roof.

22:38.160 --> 22:41.232
September the 3rd, 1943.

22:41.400 --> 22:43.356
Where did they go after?

22:43.440 --> 22:45.510
The headmistress
and the children.

22:46.160 --> 22:49.118
Not one survivor.
Poor little buggers.

22:50.040 --> 22:52.474
And they were lovely, too.

22:53.200 --> 22:56.636
Why didn't he tell us that
they all died?

22:56.800 --> 22:58.640
He leaves to join the army,
and 3 months later,

22:58.680 --> 23:00.875
everyone he knows
gets killed?

23:01.800 --> 23:04.951
Not even Grandpa could turn
that into a bedtime story.

23:05.880 --> 23:08.872
Well, no wonder he was
scared of being a dad...

23:09.040 --> 23:10.678
being close to anyone.

23:12.640 --> 23:13.789
Listen.

23:14.920 --> 23:17.115
You need to talk about all
this with someone, buddy.

23:18.120 --> 23:19.872
We should call Dr. Golan.

23:23.800 --> 23:26.155
MAN OVER TV: Certainly
some enjoyment today.

23:29.520 --> 23:30.736
Er, do you mind
if I go hang out

23:30.760 --> 23:32.159
with those
other kids today?

23:32.520 --> 23:33.520
They asked.

23:33.720 --> 23:36.234
Yeah? That's awesome.

24:33.280 --> 24:35.350
(TICKING)

25:07.400 --> 25:08.435
(GASPS)

25:11.480 --> 25:12.515
(ECHOING) Abe?

25:17.880 --> 25:18.995
(LOUD THUDDING)

25:25.360 --> 25:26.395
No!

25:26.480 --> 25:27.754
(PANTING)

25:46.640 --> 25:47.675
(GRUNTS)

25:48.520 --> 25:49.589
(GROANS)

26:01.920 --> 26:02.920
You're Emma!

26:03.600 --> 26:05.477
And the twins.

26:05.640 --> 26:06.834
And Olive.

26:07.560 --> 26:08.913
And Bronwyn.

26:09.880 --> 26:10.880
And he's Millard.

26:11.240 --> 26:12.389
Mm-hmm.

26:12.560 --> 26:13.595
No, you're dead.

26:14.120 --> 26:15.758
All of you,
you're all dead.

26:15.920 --> 26:18.673
He's invisible,
but he's still dead.

26:19.080 --> 26:20.149
None of us are dead.

26:21.760 --> 26:23.876
Oh, my God. Am I dead?

26:24.320 --> 26:25.320
No.

26:27.400 --> 26:29.550
You called me Abe.

26:30.040 --> 26:31.996
In the house. Why?

26:32.160 --> 26:33.229
You looked like him.

26:33.880 --> 26:34.880
Just for a moment,

26:34.960 --> 26:37.030
before you started
screaming...

26:37.240 --> 26:39.071
running away,
and concussing yourself.

26:39.280 --> 26:40.713
Wait. What's happening?

26:40.880 --> 26:42.336
We're waiting until
the coast is clear...

26:42.360 --> 26:43.759
before we go
into the loop.

26:45.040 --> 26:47.679
You never know
who might be watching.

26:47.840 --> 26:50.354
Wait. Before we
go into what?

26:50.520 --> 26:51.520
Please, Jake.

26:51.680 --> 26:54.035
Miss Peregrine's waiting.
She saw you on the ferry.

26:54.200 --> 26:55.315
She sent us to get you.

27:13.920 --> 27:14.955
(INDISTINCT WHISPERING)

27:15.040 --> 27:16.040
(TICKING)

27:45.880 --> 27:46.880
Hey!

27:48.120 --> 27:49.633
Where do you think
you're going?

27:50.640 --> 27:51.834
To my room.

27:53.600 --> 27:55.352
I'm a guest here.

27:55.800 --> 27:58.997
Does this look like
a hotel to you?

28:00.720 --> 28:02.073
Yeah.

28:02.280 --> 28:04.635
No. I've got a key.

28:05.640 --> 28:07.790
Talk to the manager.
He'll tell you.

28:08.640 --> 28:09.709
I'm the manager, boy.

28:10.680 --> 28:12.352
He's American.
Maybe he's army?

28:13.640 --> 28:14.675
Bollocks.

28:14.760 --> 28:16.591
Listen to his accent.
It's terrible.

28:17.800 --> 28:19.597
He's a spy.

28:20.880 --> 28:21.915
What?

28:22.000 --> 28:24.275
No, I'm not.
I'm a tourist.

28:24.440 --> 28:26.795
I say we should get
the truth out of him

28:26.880 --> 28:28.632
the old-fashioned way.

28:28.760 --> 28:29.795
(GLASS SHATTERING)

28:30.360 --> 28:31.640
(MAN SHOUTING
IN NATIVE LANGUAGE)

28:31.720 --> 28:33.438
(WOMEN SHRIEKING)

28:34.680 --> 28:35.715
WOMAN: Get down!

28:39.000 --> 28:40.035
(EXCLAIMS)

28:40.920 --> 28:42.114
(PANTING)

28:42.240 --> 28:43.355
(EXCLAIMING)

28:46.960 --> 28:48.916
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

28:49.600 --> 28:50.794
Come on!

28:59.480 --> 29:00.674
EMMA: Jake, get on!

29:03.000 --> 29:05.070
Come on! Get on, boy!

29:05.160 --> 29:07.196
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

29:15.280 --> 29:18.078
I can't believe you're real.
You're all real!

29:18.240 --> 29:19.798
We have been trying
to tell you.

29:19.960 --> 29:21.188
But I'm special, too.

29:21.320 --> 29:22.355
What?

29:22.440 --> 29:23.998
In the pub.
Olive, you saw.

29:24.160 --> 29:27.277
Right? Everything
was flying and breaking.

29:27.440 --> 29:28.440
And that was me!

29:28.840 --> 29:30.876
I was doing it
with my mind.

29:31.080 --> 29:32.911
MILLARD: No, that was me.

29:34.200 --> 29:35.200
Millard?

29:35.760 --> 29:36.909
MILLARD: Yeah.

29:37.960 --> 29:39.188
Are you naked?

29:39.280 --> 29:40.315
MILLARD: Yeah.

29:42.640 --> 29:43.640
Oh.

29:44.920 --> 29:45.955
I don't...

29:46.680 --> 29:49.114
A bomb dropped on you
in 1943.

29:49.840 --> 29:51.637
It is 1943.

29:51.800 --> 29:54.473
MILLARD:
September the 3rd, 1943.

29:54.640 --> 29:56.358
All day, every day.

29:56.560 --> 29:57.675
It's our loop.

30:30.560 --> 30:31.788
(TICKING)
Right on time.

30:33.040 --> 30:34.951
Miss Peregrine.
Delighted to meet you.

30:36.040 --> 30:37.951
I do hope I'm not going
to have the pub landlord

30:38.040 --> 30:39.917
knocking on my door
with the police again.

30:40.080 --> 30:41.672
I've had to kill them
twice this month.

30:41.840 --> 30:43.592
It's been
terribly inconvenient.

30:43.760 --> 30:45.876
Millard broke a few things.
That's all.

30:46.040 --> 30:49.555
And Olive may have
started a tiny fire.

30:51.520 --> 30:53.590
But they were going
to hurt Jake.

30:57.200 --> 30:58.952
Look at you.

30:59.120 --> 31:00.920
The last time dear Abe
sent me a photograph...

31:01.000 --> 31:02.956
you were just a tiny tot.

31:03.400 --> 31:04.719
Don't just stand there.
Come in.

31:04.840 --> 31:06.273
Your tea's getting cold.

31:08.800 --> 31:10.836
How did you know
about the pub?

31:11.000 --> 31:13.036
You weigh approximately
109 pounds, correct?

31:13.120 --> 31:14.155
I don't...

31:14.240 --> 31:16.600
Bronwyn and the twins returned
6 minutes after you ran away.

31:16.640 --> 31:18.039
I think I'm
missing something.

31:18.200 --> 31:19.296
And quite apart
from the fact

31:19.320 --> 31:20.616
that the perceived safety
of the pub...

31:20.640 --> 31:22.736
makes it the most likely place
to which you would flee...

31:22.760 --> 31:24.591
it would take you
18 minutes to run there.

31:24.760 --> 31:26.720
Emma and Millard would have
been moments behind...

31:26.800 --> 31:27.869
on the horse and trap,

31:27.960 --> 31:29.678
traveling at 8.2 miles
per hour.

31:29.840 --> 31:31.910
Factoring in some sort
of kerfuffle at the pub...

31:32.080 --> 31:34.196
and the return journey
with your added weight...

31:34.360 --> 31:37.318
you would arrive here
at 13 minutes past 4.

31:38.200 --> 31:40.509
Now, then,
do you take sugar?

31:41.160 --> 31:42.736
That'll do. Thank you, Olive.
(WHISTLING)

31:42.760 --> 31:45.194
Nobody enjoys
over-boiled tea.

31:55.160 --> 31:57.355
Let me help you
with those, Enoch.

31:57.560 --> 32:00.120
Don't bother. Wouldn't want
to interrupt your tea party.

32:10.280 --> 32:12.316
I'm so sorry
for your loss, Jake.

32:14.080 --> 32:16.036
You know, then.

32:17.400 --> 32:18.913
I know if Abe were alive,

32:19.040 --> 32:20.678
he would have told me
you were coming.

32:24.240 --> 32:26.071
Shall we take
our tea outside?

32:27.280 --> 32:28.280
Thank you.

32:30.680 --> 32:33.478
Before he died,
he told me to find you.

32:33.680 --> 32:35.318
There was something
he wanted me to know.

32:35.480 --> 32:37.038
He said you could
explain everything.

32:37.200 --> 32:38.553
That's absolutely true.

32:38.720 --> 32:41.029
There are very few things
I can't explain.

32:42.160 --> 32:44.879
We're what's known,
in common parlance,

32:44.960 --> 32:46.712
as "peculiar."

32:47.000 --> 32:48.558
(TICKING)

32:48.640 --> 32:50.312
51 seconds late, Fiona.

32:50.960 --> 32:52.029
Sorry, Miss Peregrine.

32:52.120 --> 32:53.680
How many carrots
do you need for supper?

32:54.120 --> 32:56.190
Just one will do.

33:02.400 --> 33:04.470
(RUMBLING)

33:10.520 --> 33:13.751
As I was saying,
some people are peculiar.

33:13.920 --> 33:16.912
It's a recessive gene
carried down through families.

33:17.080 --> 33:19.071
Yet, many generations
can pass

33:19.160 --> 33:21.549
without a peculiar child
being born.

33:22.760 --> 33:26.912
And alas, peculiars have been
persecuted through the ages.

33:27.080 --> 33:29.196
Hence, we live
in places like this.

33:30.200 --> 33:31.200
In Wales?

33:31.400 --> 33:33.356
Anywhere will do
if you pick the right day.

33:33.520 --> 33:35.078
That's fine now, Fiona.

33:39.000 --> 33:42.754
You see, I'm a type of
peculiar called an Ymbryne.

33:42.920 --> 33:44.273
That means I can...

33:44.440 --> 33:45.668
Yeah, you turn into a bird.

33:45.840 --> 33:47.558
I do. Yes.

33:47.720 --> 33:49.438
But that's not very useful.

33:49.600 --> 33:52.558
An Ymbryne's main skill
is the manipulation of time.

33:52.720 --> 33:54.790
We choose a safe place,
a safe day...

33:54.960 --> 33:57.076
and create a loop.

33:57.880 --> 33:59.279
What do you mean?

33:59.440 --> 34:02.796
A loop preserves
the last 24 hours.

34:02.960 --> 34:05.633
Reset the loop, and the day
is yours to live in again.

34:06.440 --> 34:07.555
Reset it daily...

34:07.720 --> 34:09.630
and you can
stay there forever.

34:09.800 --> 34:11.870
Entirely safe
from the outside world.

34:12.960 --> 34:14.552
Right on time, Bronwyn.
Good girl.

34:18.440 --> 34:19.475
(GRUNTING)

34:20.400 --> 34:21.958
And that's why we Ymbrynes

34:22.080 --> 34:23.638
are charged with the care
of the young.

34:27.080 --> 34:29.310
And no one ever gets older.

34:30.159 --> 34:32.071
It's best for everyone
this way.

34:32.159 --> 34:33.478
I assure you.

34:37.320 --> 34:38.958
Every Ymbryne
commits herself...

34:39.120 --> 34:41.270
to the creation and upkeep
of a place like this.

34:42.280 --> 34:44.953
A home for peculiar children.

34:45.159 --> 34:46.752
(TWINS GRUNTING)

34:46.840 --> 34:48.068
HUGH: You wanna muck around?

34:48.239 --> 34:49.239
MILLARD: Your bees.

34:49.440 --> 34:50.759
HUGH: Get it!

34:57.800 --> 34:59.279
You met the twins.

35:05.320 --> 35:06.514
This is Claire.

35:06.640 --> 35:07.675
(CHUCKLES)

35:11.200 --> 35:13.475
HUGH: Millard, pass the ball.
We're playing together.

35:18.360 --> 35:20.032
Millard you met.

35:20.680 --> 35:21.680
MILLARD: Ugh. Come on!

35:22.520 --> 35:23.839
And that's Hugh.

35:24.480 --> 35:25.549
(EXHALES)

35:26.360 --> 35:27.679
(MILLARD GRUNTING)

35:28.200 --> 35:29.872
MILLARD:
Stop cheating, Hugh.

35:30.640 --> 35:32.870
HUGH: Millard,
that's a foul again.

35:34.200 --> 35:36.316
MILLARD: No, it wasn't. Ref?

35:36.720 --> 35:38.711
If you two can't play soccer
without squabbling...

35:38.880 --> 35:40.393
I do wish
you wouldn't play at all.

35:40.560 --> 35:41.720
Do you know
what a referee is?

35:43.040 --> 35:44.632
Good afternoon.
I'm Horace.

35:44.800 --> 35:45.800
Delighted to meet you.

35:45.960 --> 35:47.075
MILLARD: Ow!

35:47.240 --> 35:48.240
Careful!

35:48.360 --> 35:49.873
We sorely need
some new blood here.

35:51.240 --> 35:52.309
Super shirt, by the way.

35:53.640 --> 35:54.640
Thanks.

35:54.840 --> 35:56.512
HUGH: Try harder.

35:59.400 --> 36:00.913
You know Emma, of course.

36:02.000 --> 36:03.752
And I think that's everyone.

36:04.360 --> 36:06.669
Didn't Bronwyn
have a brother?

36:07.560 --> 36:09.596
Yes. Victor's upstairs.

36:09.760 --> 36:11.120
Wait, where did Enoch
and Olive go?

36:11.880 --> 36:13.029
Heaven knows.

36:13.200 --> 36:15.560
Enoch's been off sulking ever
since we went out to get Jake.

36:15.840 --> 36:17.176
Miss Peregrine, there's
a policeman at the door.

36:17.200 --> 36:18.599
He says it's about the pub!

36:21.080 --> 36:22.752
We'll discuss this
later, Emma.

36:24.080 --> 36:25.195
(SIGHS)

36:25.280 --> 36:26.872
It wasn't their fault.

36:27.920 --> 36:30.275
Honestly, they were
just trying to help.

36:34.600 --> 36:35.715
Hmm.

36:40.240 --> 36:41.434
Thanks.

36:41.600 --> 36:43.431
You're not as wet
as I thought.

36:46.440 --> 36:50.035
She's not really gonna
kill anyone, is she?

36:50.200 --> 36:52.270
Not if she can
talk her way out of it.

36:52.480 --> 36:54.118
Would you help me
with something?

36:54.280 --> 36:55.952
Enoch usually does it,
but like I said,

36:56.080 --> 36:57.399
he's off sulking somewhere.

36:58.640 --> 37:00.198
Is that because of me?

37:00.400 --> 37:02.960
He's possessive.

37:05.280 --> 37:07.236
So, what did you
need help with?

37:08.040 --> 37:09.439
One of my daily chores.

37:09.600 --> 37:11.989
Put the baby squirrel
back in the tree.

37:12.160 --> 37:13.309
What baby squirrel?

37:19.440 --> 37:20.839
That happens every day?

37:21.000 --> 37:22.274
Like clockwork.

37:23.160 --> 37:25.200
Now, would you mind tying
that rope around my waist?

37:26.920 --> 37:27.955
Uh, yeah.

37:56.320 --> 37:58.436
Right. Promise to
hold on tight.

38:14.160 --> 38:16.469
(GRUNTS)

38:43.240 --> 38:45.071
I nearly messed that up.

38:46.520 --> 38:49.034
Abe did, too, the first time.

38:49.200 --> 38:50.918
This used to be his job.

38:53.200 --> 38:56.590
Emma, I need to
tell you something.

38:57.760 --> 38:58.909
He's dead.

39:00.560 --> 39:01.709
I know.

39:01.880 --> 39:04.440
Miss Peregrine guessed,
and she's always right.

39:05.920 --> 39:06.920
It's okay.

39:07.760 --> 39:09.910
I said goodbye to him
a long time ago.

39:10.680 --> 39:12.193
Were you close?

39:14.600 --> 39:16.238
I thought we were.

39:17.240 --> 39:18.958
For a while.

39:19.120 --> 39:20.758
But I suppose not.

39:23.120 --> 39:25.918
Can I ask, was he like you?

39:27.600 --> 39:28.749
(CHUCKLES)

39:29.080 --> 39:30.718
He was like you, Jake.

39:33.280 --> 39:34.838
I need to go
and change for supper.

39:35.440 --> 39:36.634
Will you be dining with us?

39:37.080 --> 39:38.957
I can't stay out late.

39:39.120 --> 39:40.758
Supper's at 5:30.

39:41.960 --> 39:44.110
Uh... That
is pretty early.

39:44.800 --> 39:46.392
The fact we're not
all eight years old

39:46.480 --> 39:48.118
seems to have eluded
Miss Peregrine.

39:49.240 --> 39:51.117
You can borrow
some of Abe's clothes.

39:51.320 --> 39:53.311
His room's in the attic.

40:03.640 --> 40:04.640
OLIVE: Jake!

40:05.160 --> 40:06.559
Come and meet Enoch properly.

40:17.640 --> 40:19.835
You must feel
pretty out of place.

40:21.680 --> 40:22.954
Don't worry.

40:23.520 --> 40:25.272
I'm used to it.

40:25.480 --> 40:26.629
No. I wasn't worried.

40:26.800 --> 40:29.519
Some advice for you though,
man to man.

40:29.680 --> 40:32.000
If you're thinking of staying
just because you like Emma...

40:32.360 --> 40:33.360
don't bother.

40:33.520 --> 40:35.829
You see, she swore off
romance decades ago...

40:36.000 --> 40:37.319
when she got
her heart broken.

40:38.200 --> 40:41.033
And she's never gonna
change her mind. So...

40:44.320 --> 40:45.958
Enoch, I wasn't...

40:47.880 --> 40:48.880
What are you doing?

41:19.680 --> 41:20.795
Isn't he amazing?

41:21.320 --> 41:22.389
What did you do?

41:23.080 --> 41:24.479
This?

41:24.880 --> 41:27.155
Jake, this isn't
even the fun part.

41:27.680 --> 41:28.920
Do you want to see
the fun part?

41:30.640 --> 41:32.073
(WHISPERING)

41:33.920 --> 41:35.478
(SCREECHING)

41:36.040 --> 41:37.234
(EXCLAIMS)

41:47.320 --> 41:48.514
(WHINES)

41:53.840 --> 41:54.989
ENOCH: They're like puppets.

41:55.200 --> 41:57.589
Just do anything I tell them.

41:59.840 --> 42:01.592
It's even more fun
with people.

42:01.760 --> 42:02.880
You should have seen some of

42:02.920 --> 42:04.399
the epic battles
they used to have...

42:04.560 --> 42:05.879
at my parents'
funeral parlor.

42:09.240 --> 42:10.434
You'll need a necktie.

42:19.720 --> 42:22.632
So what did my grandpa do
when he was traveling?

42:23.400 --> 42:25.197
Visited other loops.

42:25.800 --> 42:28.234
Really? To do what?

42:29.120 --> 42:30.633
Jake, there's some questions

42:30.720 --> 42:32.711
that I can't answer,
all right?

42:32.880 --> 42:34.916
So, it would be a lot easier
for me if you just...

42:35.800 --> 42:37.119
stopped asking them.

42:40.800 --> 42:42.153
(BELL DINGING)

42:42.960 --> 42:44.393
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

42:44.480 --> 42:45.993
(DOOR OPENS)

42:56.960 --> 42:58.056
MILLARD: Hey!
What are you doing?

42:58.080 --> 42:59.080
MISS PEREGRINE: Millard.

42:59.240 --> 43:01.071
Go and put some clothes on.

43:01.240 --> 43:03.310
Polite persons do not take
their supper in the nude.

43:03.480 --> 43:05.516
MILLARD: All right. All right.

43:08.680 --> 43:10.591
You can sit here, Jake.

43:12.840 --> 43:13.840
HORACE: Look at Enoch.

43:14.600 --> 43:15.669
He's jealous.

43:16.120 --> 43:17.838
Why would I be jealous?

43:18.000 --> 43:19.956
Olive can go marry Jake,
for all I care.

43:20.120 --> 43:22.509
Don't be mean, Enoch.
She doesn't want to.

43:22.680 --> 43:24.591
She's just excited
to have a visitor.

43:24.760 --> 43:26.512
Nobody is marrying anybody.

43:26.680 --> 43:28.432
Now, eat up your food
before it gets cold.

43:31.800 --> 43:33.028
(BUZZING)

43:33.320 --> 43:34.355
Hugh!

43:35.520 --> 43:37.317
(BRONWYN CLEARS THROAT)
Where's your net?

43:37.840 --> 43:40.035
FIONA: Hugh! You have to
stop doing this, Hugh.

43:43.440 --> 43:45.192
BRONWYN: Go away!
(INHALING)

43:50.720 --> 43:52.631
FIONA: Must be very strange
for you, Jake.

43:53.040 --> 43:54.951
Meeting your
grandfather's friends.

43:55.120 --> 43:56.712
Visiting another century.

43:56.880 --> 43:58.720
OLIVE: Are there spaceships
in your time, Jake?

43:58.880 --> 44:00.313
Like the Flash Gordon books.

44:00.560 --> 44:01.560
Now, now, Olive.

44:01.720 --> 44:03.392
What did I say
about asking questions?

44:04.240 --> 44:05.719
We don't discuss
the future here.

44:05.880 --> 44:08.394
We enjoy living in the
good old here and now.

44:11.680 --> 44:12.880
Claire, why aren't you eating?

44:14.320 --> 44:15.992
She's embarrassed
in front of Jake.

44:16.160 --> 44:17.718
Don't be. Please.

44:23.880 --> 44:25.916
(SNARLS, CHOMPING)

44:35.600 --> 44:37.830
So, Jake,
what's your peculiarity?

44:38.760 --> 44:40.591
(STAMMERS)
Oh, I'm not peculiar.

44:40.760 --> 44:41.909
And that, my friends,

44:42.040 --> 44:43.837
is why he will not
be staying with us...

44:44.000 --> 44:46.434
no matter how hard
we try to persuade him.

44:46.600 --> 44:49.194
We've spoken about this.
Jake is just visiting.

44:49.360 --> 44:50.588
He might want to stay.

44:50.760 --> 44:52.512
Don't you want
to stay, Jake?

44:52.960 --> 44:54.393
Tonight? Or...

44:54.560 --> 44:56.676
Forever. You should
stay forever.

44:56.880 --> 44:59.189
Why would he,
if he doesn't have to?

44:59.360 --> 45:01.396
He can live out there,
grow older...

45:01.560 --> 45:03.073
have a good time instead.

45:03.240 --> 45:05.800
He'll leave, just like
his grandfather did.

45:11.120 --> 45:12.120
Emma!

45:12.280 --> 45:13.474
MILLARD: Excuse me.

45:13.640 --> 45:14.640
Where's she going?

45:14.800 --> 45:15.949
That wasn't nice, Enoch.

45:16.080 --> 45:18.640
You know perfectly well
why Abe left us.

45:18.800 --> 45:19.800
To join the army.

45:19.960 --> 45:22.474
And then he met a lady,
and had a nice wedding cake...

45:22.640 --> 45:24.312
and a lovely little baby.

45:24.400 --> 45:25.400
Children.

45:27.320 --> 45:29.629
I know you'd all
like a new friend...

45:29.800 --> 45:33.156
but I'm sure Jake has plenty
of his own back in Florida.

45:36.000 --> 45:37.911
I think you should
all get ready

45:38.000 --> 45:40.389
for movie time
while I answer that.

45:40.560 --> 45:42.551
But you always
let us stay for it.

46:01.640 --> 46:03.119
Hello, this is Abe.

46:03.800 --> 46:05.472
How is everyone?

46:12.360 --> 46:14.080
MILLARD: Yours has extra
marshmallows, Jake.

46:14.160 --> 46:16.435
Millard, put
some pajamas on.

46:16.600 --> 46:17.953
MILLARD: It's
too hot in here.

46:18.120 --> 46:19.314
Stop moaning.

46:19.480 --> 46:20.560
MILLARD: Excuse me. (SIGHS)

46:29.000 --> 46:31.355
My grandpa
told me about this.

46:31.520 --> 46:33.875
Horace projects
his dreams, right?

46:34.040 --> 46:35.473
He used to listen
to the radio.

46:35.640 --> 46:38.359
Gets tedious when you know
every word off by heart.

46:42.480 --> 46:44.198
Splendid. I'll take it.

46:44.400 --> 46:45.879
He dreams
about clothes mostly.

46:46.040 --> 46:47.234
Delighted to meet you.

46:48.880 --> 46:50.836
Super shirt, by the way.

46:53.400 --> 46:55.231
JAKE: When did he dream this?

46:55.400 --> 46:56.674
Last night.

46:56.840 --> 46:58.398
Some of his dreams
are prophetic.

46:58.560 --> 47:00.790
But, mostly
they're about clothes.

47:02.080 --> 47:05.231
Prophetic as in,
he can see into the future?

47:16.520 --> 47:17.589
(SQUAWKS)

47:18.040 --> 47:19.155
(ALL GASP)

47:19.760 --> 47:21.432
An Ymbryne. Who is she?

47:21.600 --> 47:23.238
Miss Peregrine,
do you know her?

47:23.440 --> 47:24.440
HUGH: Don't be silly.

47:24.600 --> 47:26.750
Horace must have just had a bad dream.
That's all.

47:50.560 --> 47:52.630
(MURMURING)

47:54.080 --> 47:55.274
(GIGGLING)

47:58.120 --> 47:59.120
(CLICKS)

47:59.240 --> 48:00.559
CHILDREN: Aw!

48:01.480 --> 48:03.320
That's quite enough of that.
Thank you, Horace.

48:03.920 --> 48:05.592
I should probably
get going.

48:06.480 --> 48:08.869
You could stay the night,
if you wanted to.

48:09.040 --> 48:10.951
Rather than walk home
alone in the dark.

48:11.120 --> 48:14.317
But the island
is very safe, isn't it?

48:14.480 --> 48:15.708
Of course!

48:15.880 --> 48:18.474
I only meant the path
is dreadfully bumpy.

48:18.640 --> 48:19.789
Jake could trip.

48:20.000 --> 48:21.718
Perhaps you could show him
the shortcuts.

48:21.880 --> 48:24.758
Should he ever need
to avoid bumps.

48:25.160 --> 48:26.896
OLIVE: Won't you at least
stay to see the reset, Jake?

48:26.920 --> 48:27.920
(GROANS)

48:28.000 --> 48:29.136
It's really
quite spectacular.

48:29.160 --> 48:30.957
Yeah!
Stay, Jake!

48:31.480 --> 48:32.959
(OVERLAPPING CHATTER)

48:38.840 --> 48:40.273
MILLARD: Come on, Jake!

48:51.840 --> 48:53.910
(MUSIC PLAYING ON GRAMOPHONE)

49:02.520 --> 49:05.273
Run, rabbit, run, rabbit

49:05.360 --> 49:06.873
Run, run, run

49:06.960 --> 49:08.029
(THUNDER BREAKING)

49:08.120 --> 49:11.954
Don't give the farmer
his fun, fun, fun

49:12.040 --> 49:13.359
(TICKING)

49:13.520 --> 49:17.991
He'll get by
without his rabbit pie

49:18.440 --> 49:23.355
So run, rabbit, run, rabbit,
run, run, run

49:44.560 --> 49:46.232
(MUSIC DISTORTS)

49:46.400 --> 49:47.628
(MUSIC STOPS)

49:55.080 --> 49:57.116
(MUSIC PLAYING BACKWARDS)

50:03.920 --> 50:05.876
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

50:13.320 --> 50:14.469
(CHITTERING)

50:16.080 --> 50:18.389
Run, rabbit, run, rabbit...

50:18.480 --> 50:22.439
Bang, bang, bang, bang
goes the farmer's gun

50:24.800 --> 50:27.712
Don't give the farmer
his fun, fun, fun

50:28.920 --> 50:30.035
(CHUCKLES)

50:30.120 --> 50:33.430
He'll get by
without his rabbit pie

50:33.560 --> 50:35.198
That was fantastic.

50:35.280 --> 50:36.872
(OVERLAPPING CHATTER)

51:11.640 --> 51:12.709
(CELL PHONE CHIMES)

51:12.840 --> 51:13.989
What was that?

51:14.160 --> 51:15.832
It was my phone.

51:16.000 --> 51:18.753
It's been dead the whole time in the loop.
I guess now...

51:18.920 --> 51:20.239
Your phone?

51:20.920 --> 51:23.480
Yeah. Like a telephone.

51:23.680 --> 51:25.989
You can call people...

51:26.160 --> 51:28.151
send written messages.

51:28.320 --> 51:30.151
Wait, you'll love this.

51:30.320 --> 51:31.912
You can take a picture.

51:32.080 --> 51:34.355
Press that, there. Yeah.

51:34.480 --> 51:35.480
(SHUTTER CLICKS)

51:35.920 --> 51:36.989
See?

51:38.280 --> 51:39.349
(CHUCKLES)

51:44.160 --> 51:45.639
What's wrong?

51:48.280 --> 51:51.670
It's just funny to think
that one day, you'll grow up.

51:51.840 --> 51:53.034
Like Abe did.

51:53.760 --> 51:56.354
Get married, have children.

51:56.520 --> 51:57.669
Grandchildren.

51:58.440 --> 52:00.590
You might even show them
this photograph.

52:02.000 --> 52:03.479
And I'll still be here.

52:05.400 --> 52:07.595
Couldn't you leave
some day?

52:07.760 --> 52:10.513
And live in the present,
if you wanted to?

52:10.680 --> 52:11.680
No.

52:12.120 --> 52:13.496
More than a few minutes
in your time

52:13.520 --> 52:15.158
and the years
would catch up.

52:16.600 --> 52:18.079
You would age?

52:19.160 --> 52:20.957
(STAMMERS)
(FLUTTERING)

52:22.200 --> 52:23.349
(SQUAWKING)

52:26.680 --> 52:28.750
I think it's the Ymbryne
from Horace's dream.

52:29.240 --> 52:31.993
JAKE: Are you sure
it's not just a bird?

52:32.240 --> 52:33.673
I don't know,
wouldn't it change?

52:33.840 --> 52:36.070
She can't.
Not if she's hurt.

52:37.080 --> 52:39.753
I need to take her inside.
You should go.

52:43.240 --> 52:44.673
Please don't say
anything else.

52:44.760 --> 52:46.318
I hate goodbyes.

52:49.240 --> 52:50.240
I'll come back tomorrow.

52:51.520 --> 52:54.830
There's no hurry.
I'll be here forever.

53:02.440 --> 53:03.440
Hey!

53:05.560 --> 53:06.736
I've been all over
this damn island.

53:06.760 --> 53:07.875
Where the hell were you?

53:08.080 --> 53:10.116
Um, I was just
on my way back.

53:10.280 --> 53:11.918
I'm sorry.
I lost track of time.

53:12.960 --> 53:15.428
I was having a blast
with Worm and Dirty D.

53:16.360 --> 53:17.429
Dirty D?

53:18.520 --> 53:19.714
You know what?

53:19.920 --> 53:22.070
This is good.
This is healthy.

53:22.240 --> 53:23.912
You're making
weird friends...

53:24.960 --> 53:26.951
and doing teenage stuff.

53:27.120 --> 53:28.120
I think this is normal.

53:28.240 --> 53:29.719
I'm sure Doctor Golan
will approve.

53:29.880 --> 53:31.598
FARMER: Hey, you.
American!

53:31.760 --> 53:32.954
Get over here.

53:34.880 --> 53:35.949
Oh, look.
There they are.

53:36.120 --> 53:39.317
There's D-Bag
and Worm Man.

53:39.480 --> 53:40.595
Did you do this?

53:42.080 --> 53:44.310
What? No.

53:44.920 --> 53:45.955
Of course not.

53:46.480 --> 53:47.595
It wasn't us.

53:48.240 --> 53:49.936
Listen, sir. I don't know
what happened here.

53:49.960 --> 53:52.997
But my son and his friends
have been together all day.

53:53.160 --> 53:55.435
Jake would never
do anything like this.

53:55.600 --> 53:57.113
Bollocks!
We haven't seen him!

53:57.280 --> 53:58.395
You paid us yesterday.

53:58.480 --> 54:00.311
Why would we hang out
with him today for free?

54:03.160 --> 54:06.152
Jake? Were you with
them or not?

54:07.520 --> 54:09.636
No. I'm sorry.

54:10.640 --> 54:12.471
But you don't seriously
think I could do this?

54:13.720 --> 54:15.312
I think we're
done here, sir.

54:16.840 --> 54:18.990
FRANK: Can you pass on
a message for me?

54:19.160 --> 54:21.151
Can you tell
Doctor Golan...

54:21.360 --> 54:23.715
that if she hadn't encouraged
this cockamamie trip...

54:23.880 --> 54:25.029
maybe my son wouldn't be

54:25.160 --> 54:26.856
moping around all day
in a derelict house...

54:26.880 --> 54:28.711
having a
goddamn breakdown!

54:29.680 --> 54:30.829
Hello?

54:31.000 --> 54:32.513
Dad, I'm not.

54:33.320 --> 54:34.320
I'm fine.

54:34.480 --> 54:36.198
No. You're not.

54:37.320 --> 54:39.311
You're not fine, Jake.

54:40.360 --> 54:42.999
Coming here was a
terrible, terrible idea.

54:43.680 --> 54:45.636
Look, I'm sorry I lied.
I just wanted...

54:45.840 --> 54:48.308
Just set your alarm
for 8:00 a.m.

54:48.760 --> 54:50.716
I wanna get
to the beach early.

54:50.880 --> 54:51.976
The rest of the time
we're stuck

54:52.000 --> 54:53.149
on this craphole island...

54:53.320 --> 54:54.719
we're sticking together.

54:56.000 --> 54:57.035
Where are you going?

54:57.200 --> 54:59.236
Downstairs for a drink.

55:48.120 --> 55:49.200
ABE: Dear Miss Peregrine...

55:49.720 --> 55:51.392
I don't wish to alarm you...

55:51.560 --> 55:54.120
but one of my informants
sent me this.

55:54.880 --> 55:57.394
It would appear that some
of Mr. Barron's group...

55:57.560 --> 55:59.391
are in Blackpool, England.

56:00.600 --> 56:01.953
If I recall...

56:02.120 --> 56:04.429
Miss Avocet has a loop there.

56:05.080 --> 56:06.991
Please warn her and suggest...

56:07.160 --> 56:08.991
that she make a new one
right away...

56:09.160 --> 56:10.275
well-hidden.

56:10.440 --> 56:13.000
And take
the greatest care yourself.

56:13.160 --> 56:14.912
With love, Abe.

56:15.080 --> 56:17.071
January, 2016.

56:19.480 --> 56:21.471
(CELL PHONE RINGING)

56:36.000 --> 56:37.513
Who's ready
to hit the beach?

56:37.640 --> 56:38.914
Ugh.

56:40.520 --> 56:42.317
(BIRDS SQUAWKING)

56:44.200 --> 56:45.679
Oh, my... (CHUCKLES)

56:46.360 --> 56:47.360
Unbelievable.

56:49.160 --> 56:51.037
Right in the middle
of a nesting area?

56:51.200 --> 56:53.475
What kind of idiot
does that?

56:54.840 --> 56:57.673
Actually, the main
nesting area is over there.

56:58.280 --> 56:59.838
I can show you
if you'd like.

57:00.000 --> 57:02.195
It's marvelous to meet
a fellow bird spotter.

57:02.320 --> 57:03.355
John Lamont.

57:03.560 --> 57:05.630
Franklin Portman.
This is my son, Jake.

57:06.360 --> 57:07.509
John Lamont.

57:07.680 --> 57:09.240
That's a hell of a camera
you got there.

57:10.040 --> 57:12.679
Oh, thanks.
It's absolutely fantastic.

57:12.840 --> 57:16.196
I'm here to do some snaps
for a book I'm writing.

57:16.360 --> 57:18.191
So, you gentlemen here
on holiday?

57:21.640 --> 57:24.154
MAN: Unfortunately,
her wings were flapping

57:24.240 --> 57:25.275
as much as the bird's!

57:25.360 --> 57:26.395
(MEN LAUGHING)

57:27.480 --> 57:28.560
MAN: I think you fellas are

57:28.640 --> 57:29.856
thinking of another kind
of bird.

57:29.880 --> 57:31.440
So, you're not going
to the beach today?

57:32.040 --> 57:33.359
What's the point?

57:33.520 --> 57:35.112
If that guy is gonna
cover Cairnholm

57:35.200 --> 57:36.679
in some big, glossy book...

57:36.840 --> 57:38.478
no one's gonna even
wanna look at mine.

57:40.000 --> 57:41.911
Might just have
a nice afternoon nap.

57:42.760 --> 57:44.273
I don't suppose
you saw Uncle Oggie

57:44.360 --> 57:46.191
on your travels
this morning, did you?

57:46.400 --> 57:47.913
He's usually here by now.

57:48.080 --> 57:49.195
I could go look for him.

57:49.920 --> 57:51.399
You're not going anywhere.

57:53.840 --> 57:55.193
(FRANK SNORING)

58:07.520 --> 58:09.192
(WHISPERING)

58:27.080 --> 58:29.435
Jake, you're back!
Come and play!

58:30.600 --> 58:31.600
Oh!
(BRONWYN GIGGLING)

58:34.120 --> 58:36.076
I need to see
Miss Peregrine first.

58:36.240 --> 58:37.593
Do you know where she is?

58:37.760 --> 58:39.416
WINSTON CHURCHILL OVER RADIO:
From the darkest days,

58:39.440 --> 58:40.589
the Canadian army...

58:40.760 --> 58:42.273
(CHIRPING)

58:42.920 --> 58:45.559
Jake. You're back.
How wonderful!

58:46.280 --> 58:47.280
How's it doing?

58:47.920 --> 58:49.239
Emma said it was an Ymbryne.

58:49.800 --> 58:51.233
"She." Not "it."

58:51.400 --> 58:53.277
Ymbrynes are
always female.

58:53.440 --> 58:54.839
And Emma was quite correct.

58:55.000 --> 58:56.592
This is Miss Avocet.

58:56.800 --> 58:59.553
Her loop's in Blackpool.
England.

59:02.280 --> 59:04.430
That was a
private letter, Jake.

59:07.160 --> 59:08.639
Who is Mr. Barron?

59:11.640 --> 59:13.073
Miss Peregrine,
if my Grandpa

59:13.160 --> 59:15.116
was involved
with dangerous people...

59:15.320 --> 59:16.833
I need to tell the police.

59:18.120 --> 59:19.120
Police?

59:20.320 --> 59:22.675
Are you implying Abe
died an unnatural death?

59:23.200 --> 59:24.792
I found him in the woods...

59:24.960 --> 59:26.996
with his eyes missing.

59:27.160 --> 59:28.991
I'd say that was
pretty unnatural.

59:33.640 --> 59:36.837
Unless essential, I don't
discuss unpleasant matters.

59:37.000 --> 59:39.468
An Ymbryne's duty is to
protect children, Jake.

59:40.680 --> 59:42.272
I'm not a child.

59:43.320 --> 59:45.880
He wanted you
to tell me everything!

59:50.880 --> 59:52.836
Oh. How frustrating
for you.

59:53.360 --> 59:54.713
Between Miss Peregrine's
rules...

59:54.880 --> 59:57.000
and my housemates' little
pact not to scare you off...

59:57.040 --> 59:59.156
it's like no one's
telling you anything!

01:00:00.520 --> 01:00:02.317
Why don't you, then?

01:00:02.400 --> 01:00:03.833
It's not like
you want me here.

01:00:04.360 --> 01:00:06.828
Enoch, you can't.
You promised.

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:09.194
Olive's right.

01:00:10.040 --> 01:00:11.336
I do know someone
who can get away

01:00:11.360 --> 01:00:12.713
with breaking rules though.

01:00:13.360 --> 01:00:14.634
Want to meet him?

01:00:16.080 --> 01:00:18.640
Enoch, don't
do this. Please!

01:00:18.840 --> 01:00:20.176
You want to spend time
with me and Jake,

01:00:20.200 --> 01:00:21.349
we can all play together.

01:00:21.520 --> 01:00:22.839
That's what you said.

01:00:24.200 --> 01:00:25.918
Here we all are.

01:00:27.200 --> 01:00:28.872
Move, Olive.

01:00:29.040 --> 01:00:30.280
If you're going
to be like that,

01:00:30.360 --> 01:00:32.669
then I don't want
to be your friend.

01:00:35.440 --> 01:00:39.399
Enoch, leave Victor alone.
It really upsets Bronwyn.

01:00:39.560 --> 01:00:41.357
Stop fussing, Fiona.

01:00:41.440 --> 01:00:43.120
Don't you think Jake
should meet everybody?

01:00:43.240 --> 01:00:44.760
He's trying to frighten
you away, Jake.

01:00:44.880 --> 01:00:47.678
He was always jealous of Abe.
And now he's jealous of you.

01:00:47.840 --> 01:00:49.239
Come and play
with us instead.

01:00:53.440 --> 01:00:56.273
I'd quite like
to meet Victor.

01:01:02.880 --> 01:01:04.074
After you.

01:01:12.600 --> 01:01:13.635
Hello, Victor.

01:01:14.760 --> 01:01:17.877
I'm Jake.
I'm sorry to disturb...

01:01:21.560 --> 01:01:22.788
ENOCH:
Yeah, he can't hear you.

01:01:48.280 --> 01:01:50.157
Hello, Jake. I'm Victor.

01:01:50.280 --> 01:01:51.679
Do you want to know
what killed me?

01:01:59.640 --> 01:02:01.471
There you are.
Is Enoch with you?

01:02:01.600 --> 01:02:03.079
It's time for
our daily walk.

01:02:06.080 --> 01:02:08.469
Emma, who killed Victor?

01:02:08.640 --> 01:02:10.312
Was it the people
with the white eyes?

01:02:10.480 --> 01:02:12.118
I asked you
not to ask questions.

01:02:12.280 --> 01:02:15.272
I saw one the night
my grandpa died.

01:02:15.440 --> 01:02:16.475
A man.

01:02:18.440 --> 01:02:19.475
If it really was one,

01:02:19.600 --> 01:02:21.192
you have to
tell Miss Peregrine.

01:02:21.360 --> 01:02:23.476
Could you recognize him
from a photograph?

01:02:23.640 --> 01:02:25.039
Do you have one?

01:02:26.360 --> 01:02:28.316
Come on. There's somewhere
I go to be alone.

01:02:28.440 --> 01:02:29.873
I have things there.

01:03:04.680 --> 01:03:05.749
(TICKING)

01:03:07.240 --> 01:03:08.514
Is this the place?

01:03:08.720 --> 01:03:10.870
No. This is how we get there.

01:03:30.400 --> 01:03:32.231
Oh! Emma! Your shoes!

01:03:32.400 --> 01:03:33.833
Lead shoes!

01:03:59.240 --> 01:04:00.434
(GASPS)

01:05:27.560 --> 01:05:28.560
(GASPING)

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:31.831
(EMMA PANTING)

01:05:35.840 --> 01:05:37.353
Welcome to my
secret hideout.

01:05:39.720 --> 01:05:41.472
How did you...

01:05:41.560 --> 01:05:42.629
Air.

01:05:43.360 --> 01:05:44.998
It's my peculiarity.

01:05:45.640 --> 01:05:47.517
It does what I want.

01:06:06.560 --> 01:06:07.754
Jake...

01:06:07.920 --> 01:06:09.558
before your
grandfather retired...

01:06:09.720 --> 01:06:11.870
he asked me
to keep this safe.

01:06:30.040 --> 01:06:31.359
This is my grandpa's
old map.

01:06:31.520 --> 01:06:33.078
It shows you
where the loops are.

01:06:44.360 --> 01:06:45.918
That's him!

01:06:46.080 --> 01:06:47.752
That's the man I saw.

01:06:48.200 --> 01:06:49.918
Who is he?
That's Barron.

01:06:50.080 --> 01:06:51.080
He's the leader.

01:06:52.400 --> 01:06:53.753
The leader of what?

01:06:54.600 --> 01:06:55.794
Who are these people?

01:06:57.080 --> 01:06:59.913
Bad people. Bad peculiars.

01:07:00.720 --> 01:07:03.598
Abe dedicated his life
to hunting them down.

01:07:03.760 --> 01:07:05.591
These are the ones
he never found.

01:07:06.440 --> 01:07:08.271
What do you mean, hunting?

01:07:11.280 --> 01:07:13.077
They raided loops.

01:07:13.240 --> 01:07:16.630
Whole homes full of children
left for dead.

01:07:17.120 --> 01:07:19.315
Abe took lives
to save lives.

01:07:19.480 --> 01:07:22.313
He only retired when you were
born to protect you.

01:07:23.400 --> 01:07:24.469
From what?

01:07:28.600 --> 01:07:29.669
If I tell you the rest,

01:07:29.800 --> 01:07:31.836
you have to promise
not to run away.

01:07:33.080 --> 01:07:36.117
Jake, you belong here.

01:07:36.320 --> 01:07:37.673
You know I don't.

01:07:37.840 --> 01:07:39.796
I'm not like you.

01:07:40.480 --> 01:07:41.754
I'm just ordinary.

01:07:41.920 --> 01:07:43.273
No, you're not.

01:07:43.440 --> 01:07:44.475
Jake...

01:07:44.640 --> 01:07:47.518
only a peculiar
can enter a time loop.

01:07:50.160 --> 01:07:52.151
No. That can't be right.

01:07:52.800 --> 01:07:54.199
I would know.

01:07:55.160 --> 01:07:56.160
Fine.

01:07:58.160 --> 01:07:59.832
Then I'll show you
something else.

01:08:07.320 --> 01:08:08.469
Hurry. You'll miss it.

01:08:22.319 --> 01:08:25.676
Ymbrynes usually pick the
perfect day to create a loop.

01:08:25.840 --> 01:08:27.800
But Miss Peregrine had to
make this one in a rush.

01:08:29.080 --> 01:08:30.080
Why?

01:08:30.720 --> 01:08:32.895
Because the Germans were about
to drop a bomb on the house.

01:08:32.920 --> 01:08:34.353
The point is...

01:08:34.520 --> 01:08:37.353
September the 3rd, 1943
wasn't perfect.

01:08:38.680 --> 01:08:40.910
The thing that killed
Victor came back.

01:09:01.399 --> 01:09:02.879
(GROWLING)

01:09:08.080 --> 01:09:09.115
(SHOUTS) Wait! Watch out!

01:09:09.880 --> 01:09:11.108
You'll put her off!

01:09:29.880 --> 01:09:30.915
(SCREECHES)

01:09:39.640 --> 01:09:41.392
You can see it, can't you?

01:09:41.920 --> 01:09:43.433
No one else can.

01:09:43.920 --> 01:09:46.069
It's invisible, Jake.

01:09:46.279 --> 01:09:47.680
That was Abe's
greatest gift of all.

01:09:50.880 --> 01:09:52.438
He could see the monsters.

01:09:57.760 --> 01:09:59.751
We call them Hollowgast.

01:09:59.960 --> 01:10:01.109
Hollows for short.

01:10:01.960 --> 01:10:05.919
My grandpa told me about
people who turn into monsters.

01:10:06.080 --> 01:10:07.433
Is that what they are?

01:10:08.400 --> 01:10:10.436
I will explain
everything, Jake.

01:10:10.640 --> 01:10:12.756
I fear it's my duty now,
considering.

01:10:12.920 --> 01:10:13.976
But you should know
that in doing so,

01:10:14.000 --> 01:10:15.160
I'm breaking
a solemn promise.

01:10:18.000 --> 01:10:19.956
I knew you were peculiar
when you were born.

01:10:20.480 --> 01:10:22.835
But your grandfather forbid
me to tell you anything.

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:26.310
His dearest wish was for you
to have an ordinary childhood.

01:10:26.840 --> 01:10:28.637
I definitely had that.

01:10:28.800 --> 01:10:31.314
He intended to tell you the
truth when you turned 18.

01:10:31.840 --> 01:10:36.311
He hoped his bedtime stories
would pave the way.

01:10:37.000 --> 01:10:38.035
Ah.

01:10:38.160 --> 01:10:39.513
Here's my book.

01:10:50.880 --> 01:10:52.359
Many years ago...

01:10:53.040 --> 01:10:55.793
a splinter faction emerged
among our people.

01:10:55.960 --> 01:10:58.520
Disaffected peculiars
tired of living in loops.

01:10:59.200 --> 01:11:01.634
That's Mr. Barron.

01:11:01.800 --> 01:11:03.836
He believed that
by harnessing the essence

01:11:03.960 --> 01:11:05.552
of an Ymbryne's powers...

01:11:05.720 --> 01:11:08.473
he and his cronies
could gain immortality...

01:11:08.640 --> 01:11:10.995
and be able
to live outside loops.

01:11:11.200 --> 01:11:13.316
He devised an experiment.

01:11:16.480 --> 01:11:18.311
He kidnapped an Ymbryne...

01:11:18.400 --> 01:11:19.400
not knowing or caring

01:11:19.520 --> 01:11:21.351
whether she would survive
the experiment.

01:11:21.800 --> 01:11:23.518
(CRANKING)

01:11:42.680 --> 01:11:44.796
But the fate of Barron
and his group

01:11:44.880 --> 01:11:46.279
was more horrifying still.

01:11:54.280 --> 01:11:55.349
(CHOKING)

01:11:55.440 --> 01:11:57.237
(GROANING)

01:12:01.520 --> 01:12:03.078
(GROANING)

01:12:03.520 --> 01:12:05.238
(SCREAMING)

01:12:05.880 --> 01:12:07.552
(SCREAMING)

01:12:08.080 --> 01:12:10.196
(GROANING, SCREAMING)

01:12:12.720 --> 01:12:14.392
(SCREAMS, GROWLING)

01:12:19.240 --> 01:12:20.878
(SCREAMING)

01:12:21.720 --> 01:12:23.073
(SCREAMING CONTINUES)

01:12:23.600 --> 01:12:25.909
Why didn't Barron
turn into one?

01:12:26.040 --> 01:12:27.439
(SCREAMING)

01:12:28.800 --> 01:12:30.597
(HOWLING)

01:12:39.400 --> 01:12:40.799
He did.

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:42.592
But years later...

01:12:42.760 --> 01:12:44.955
he found a way
to reverse the effects.

01:12:45.120 --> 01:12:46.599
To regain humanity.

01:12:46.760 --> 01:12:50.116
They had become not
immortal gods, but Hollows.

01:12:50.280 --> 01:12:52.589
Invisible beasts, dangerous...

01:12:52.800 --> 01:12:54.791
cold-blooded, deadly.

01:12:54.960 --> 01:12:56.680
EMMA: Remember I told you
they raided loops?

01:12:57.640 --> 01:12:58.834
This is why.

01:12:59.440 --> 01:13:01.440
MISS PEREGRINE: Barron
discovered that by consuming

01:13:01.520 --> 01:13:03.670
the eyes of other peculiars...

01:13:03.840 --> 01:13:05.956
especially children...

01:13:06.440 --> 01:13:08.112
(GROWLING)
(SHRIEKS)

01:13:13.440 --> 01:13:14.998
he began to change.

01:13:25.800 --> 01:13:27.313
(GOBBLING)

01:13:28.600 --> 01:13:30.033
(CHOMPING)

01:13:33.280 --> 01:13:34.599
Consume enough, and a Hollow

01:13:34.720 --> 01:13:36.472
can fully regain
its human form.

01:13:36.680 --> 01:13:37.999
Bon appetit.

01:13:38.680 --> 01:13:41.035
MISS PEREGRINE: Just as Barron
and some of his friends did.

01:13:42.960 --> 01:13:43.995
(SIGHS) Mmm.

01:13:50.360 --> 01:13:52.157
The rest of them
are stuck as Hollows.

01:13:54.720 --> 01:13:58.190
Are you saying
that Barron ate my grand...

01:13:58.360 --> 01:14:00.056
MISS PEREGRINE: He needs
no more eyes himself.

01:14:00.080 --> 01:14:03.834
But I fear he led a Hollow
to your grandfather. Yes.

01:14:05.640 --> 01:14:07.995
After the first attacks
on loops...

01:14:08.160 --> 01:14:10.515
we all got better at hiding,
making new loops,

01:14:10.640 --> 01:14:12.198
keeping our
whereabouts secret.

01:14:13.480 --> 01:14:15.869
The Hollows grow more
desperate every year...

01:14:16.040 --> 01:14:18.679
and Barron wishes
to help his friends.

01:14:18.840 --> 01:14:21.070
Miss Peregrine, come quickly.
Miss Avocet's awake.

01:14:22.000 --> 01:14:23.360
(MISS AVOCET SPEAKING
INDISTINCTLY)

01:14:24.880 --> 01:14:26.438
And suddenly,
I flew into it again...

01:14:26.600 --> 01:14:28.830
Bang! Bang!
I couldn't see anything.

01:14:29.400 --> 01:14:31.868
Oh, Miss Peregrine.
They found my new loop.

01:14:32.040 --> 01:14:34.918
The children.
I tried to save them...

01:14:35.080 --> 01:14:36.672
but there were
so many Hollows.

01:14:36.840 --> 01:14:38.558
I don't know how I escaped.

01:14:41.080 --> 01:14:42.229
You're safe now.

01:14:42.400 --> 01:14:44.231
None of us are safe.

01:14:44.400 --> 01:14:46.356
They set up the machine
in my loop.

01:14:46.520 --> 01:14:48.511
They put it in the cellars
at Blackpool Tower.

01:14:48.680 --> 01:14:49.908
They're still there.

01:14:50.080 --> 01:14:51.911
Their machine?
The experiment.

01:14:52.080 --> 01:14:54.514
They intend to do it again.

01:14:54.680 --> 01:14:56.750
This time, he's using
more Ymbrynes.

01:14:56.920 --> 01:14:58.797
He still wants
to be immortal.

01:15:02.880 --> 01:15:04.791
Do Hollows
only attack peculiars?

01:15:04.960 --> 01:15:06.188
Of course not.

01:15:07.040 --> 01:15:08.314
They're monsters, Jake.

01:15:08.440 --> 01:15:10.590
They'll slaughter anything
in their path.

01:15:10.760 --> 01:15:13.035
Some sheep on the island
were killed.

01:15:13.600 --> 01:15:15.795
You don't think they're here
already, do you?

01:15:16.320 --> 01:15:18.231
Have you seen anyone
with white eyes?

01:15:22.800 --> 01:15:24.756
I'm sorry, children.
We can't remain here.

01:15:24.920 --> 01:15:25.920
What?

01:15:26.120 --> 01:15:28.280
We'll leave on the first ferry
off the island tomorrow.

01:15:28.440 --> 01:15:30.112
Pack anything
of importance.

01:15:30.240 --> 01:15:31.958
Then it's sandwiches
and early to bed.

01:15:32.120 --> 01:15:33.439
Are we leaving for good?

01:15:33.600 --> 01:15:35.272
When are we coming back?
Never.

01:15:35.440 --> 01:15:36.520
If Miss Peregrine's
not here

01:15:36.600 --> 01:15:37.999
to reset the loop
tomorrow night...

01:15:38.160 --> 01:15:39.160
the house gets bombed.

01:15:39.320 --> 01:15:40.469
But our house.

01:15:40.680 --> 01:15:41.715
Don't cry.

01:15:41.800 --> 01:15:42.920
Miss Peregrine will find you

01:15:42.960 --> 01:15:44.400
another lovely house,
somewhere else.

01:15:51.560 --> 01:15:53.437
Once this loop closes,
that's it.

01:15:53.600 --> 01:15:55.397
I can't get back
to my own time.

01:15:55.880 --> 01:15:57.438
You didn't seem
very happy there.

01:15:57.600 --> 01:16:00.956
I can't just leave!
I have a family!

01:16:01.160 --> 01:16:02.513
And you felt ordinary.

01:16:02.680 --> 01:16:05.114
Like, nothing you do
changes anything!

01:16:05.280 --> 01:16:06.872
Now you have a chance
to do something

01:16:06.960 --> 01:16:08.393
that changes everything!

01:16:09.320 --> 01:16:11.311
Jake, we're in danger.

01:16:11.480 --> 01:16:13.948
And you're the only one
who can see the Hollows.

01:16:14.120 --> 01:16:17.157
Yeah, see them, sure.
But I'm not my grandpa!

01:16:18.160 --> 01:16:20.355
I'm not, and I can't fight.

01:16:20.520 --> 01:16:22.112
I can't kill somebody.

01:16:25.920 --> 01:16:28.559
There's only one reason
that I'd stay here...

01:16:28.720 --> 01:16:29.720
Please.

01:16:30.760 --> 01:16:32.273
Just go.

01:17:00.800 --> 01:17:03.360
Jake? Jakey,
there you are.

01:17:03.520 --> 01:17:04.555
Thank God!

01:17:04.760 --> 01:17:06.955
When I heard they found
a body, I freaked.

01:17:31.600 --> 01:17:33.272
Are there stray dogs
around here?

01:17:34.120 --> 01:17:35.120
What you talking about?

01:17:36.640 --> 01:17:38.198
It's like...

01:17:38.360 --> 01:17:39.839
when they find
an injured animal,

01:17:39.920 --> 01:17:41.990
they go for
the soft parts first.

01:17:43.480 --> 01:17:45.072
Same thing happened
to my father.

01:17:45.840 --> 01:17:48.035
The police are
on their way.

01:17:49.160 --> 01:17:50.434
Look, Dad. I've gotta go.

01:17:50.640 --> 01:17:52.676
What? No.
You don't, Jake.

01:17:53.400 --> 01:17:54.480
If this wasn't an accident,

01:17:54.560 --> 01:17:55.800
there's a lunatic
on the island.

01:17:56.280 --> 01:17:58.840
I've known everyone on
this island my whole life.

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:00.877
Except you, and him.

01:18:01.440 --> 01:18:02.856
And he's been in the pub
all afternoon.

01:18:02.880 --> 01:18:04.791
So have I.
I was sleeping.

01:18:04.960 --> 01:18:06.640
ORNITHOLOGIST: What
about the blind fellow?

01:18:06.760 --> 01:18:09.149
I assumed he was blind.

01:18:09.320 --> 01:18:10.878
Gentleman with
the dark glasses...

01:18:11.080 --> 01:18:13.036
arrived on
the same ferry as me?

01:18:13.200 --> 01:18:15.077
I kept seeing him around.

01:18:15.800 --> 01:18:16.835
Jake!

01:18:17.600 --> 01:18:18.635
Jake!

01:18:19.320 --> 01:18:22.437
Jake! Wait! (SIGHS)

01:18:24.280 --> 01:18:26.191
(PANTING)

01:18:26.880 --> 01:18:28.233
Is your son all right?

01:18:28.400 --> 01:18:29.400
No.

01:18:29.480 --> 01:18:32.790
He has mental
health issues.

01:18:32.960 --> 01:18:33.995
I can't go.

01:18:34.080 --> 01:18:36.469
Let me.
I run 5-Ks all the time.

01:18:50.400 --> 01:18:51.400
ORNITHOLOGIST: Hello?

01:18:56.040 --> 01:18:57.075
Hello?

01:18:58.120 --> 01:18:59.439
Is that you, young man?

01:19:01.200 --> 01:19:02.519
You came through...

01:19:03.480 --> 01:19:04.833
You're peculiar?

01:19:05.960 --> 01:19:07.109
Oh, yes.

01:19:08.120 --> 01:19:11.032
And I'm extremely
grateful to you.

01:19:11.760 --> 01:19:14.228
Terribly hard to find loops
these days.

01:19:15.200 --> 01:19:17.998
So, you followed me from
the beach on purpose?

01:19:18.600 --> 01:19:19.794
Oh, no.

01:19:20.400 --> 01:19:23.312
I've been following you
much further than that.

01:19:28.600 --> 01:19:30.079
Doctor Golan?

01:19:30.600 --> 01:19:31.669
Sometimes.

01:19:32.320 --> 01:19:33.719
When it suits me.

01:19:34.560 --> 01:19:37.438
The breadth
of my peculiarity...

01:19:37.600 --> 01:19:40.512
is purely limited
by my imagination.

01:19:41.440 --> 01:19:43.635
The only thing
I can't change...

01:19:46.520 --> 01:19:48.317
is my eyes.

01:19:54.320 --> 01:19:56.788
Mr. Barron. How do you do?

01:20:00.240 --> 01:20:03.277
I saw you
at your grandfather's.

01:20:04.160 --> 01:20:05.195
I was hoping to get

01:20:05.320 --> 01:20:06.536
Miss Peregrine's
address from him.

01:20:06.560 --> 01:20:08.357
But, alas,
my traveling companion

01:20:08.440 --> 01:20:10.237
got to him before I did.

01:20:10.960 --> 01:20:12.154
As you know...

01:20:12.320 --> 01:20:15.869
there's just no stopping
a hungry Hollowgast!

01:20:15.960 --> 01:20:17.154
(LAUGHING)
(GRUNTS)

01:20:18.080 --> 01:20:19.149
(GASPS)

01:20:19.480 --> 01:20:22.313
Speaking of
my traveling companion...

01:20:23.880 --> 01:20:24.915
he's coming.

01:20:25.320 --> 01:20:27.914
Believe me
when I say to you...

01:20:28.080 --> 01:20:30.913
you don't want to be here...

01:20:31.080 --> 01:20:33.116
when he arrives.

01:20:34.480 --> 01:20:37.631
So, let's be on our way.

01:20:38.760 --> 01:20:39.795
Shall we?

01:20:45.480 --> 01:20:46.833
MILLARD: Excuse me.

01:20:51.760 --> 01:20:52.795
Wait for me.

01:20:57.160 --> 01:20:58.496
MISS PEREGRINE: I mustn't
forget our calendar.

01:20:58.520 --> 01:20:59.656
Could you fetch it
from the parlor

01:20:59.680 --> 01:21:00.829
please, Miss Avocet?

01:21:04.720 --> 01:21:06.153
Go and help the others.

01:21:08.960 --> 01:21:10.234
(BELL DINGING)

01:21:19.520 --> 01:21:21.590
Miss Peregrine,
what a pleasure

01:21:21.680 --> 01:21:22.954
to meet you at last!

01:21:24.240 --> 01:21:26.037
May we come in?

01:21:32.920 --> 01:21:34.035
Children!

01:21:34.440 --> 01:21:37.352
Would you make your way
down the stairs, please?

01:21:37.520 --> 01:21:40.273
I give the orders
in this house, Mr. Barron.

01:21:40.440 --> 01:21:41.509
BARRON: Not today.

01:21:42.000 --> 01:21:45.470
You should know that Jake
has served his purpose.

01:21:45.640 --> 01:21:47.358
If you value his life,
I suggest

01:21:47.440 --> 01:21:49.829
everyone does
as they're told.

01:21:50.000 --> 01:21:51.558
Children!
Shush!

01:21:52.640 --> 01:21:55.359
No one tells my children
what to do!

01:21:57.040 --> 01:21:58.040
Children...

01:21:58.440 --> 01:22:00.396
come down here, please.

01:22:03.720 --> 01:22:04.755
Miss Peregrine...

01:22:04.840 --> 01:22:06.671
I thought I told you
to be quiet.

01:22:09.560 --> 01:22:10.629
Children...

01:22:10.800 --> 01:22:12.756
for Jake's safety...

01:22:12.920 --> 01:22:15.388
we're going to do
what Mr. Barron asks.

01:22:16.080 --> 01:22:17.308
He wishes
to take me with him

01:22:17.400 --> 01:22:18.879
to his rendezvous
in Blackpool.

01:22:19.040 --> 01:22:20.632
So, for his protection...

01:22:20.800 --> 01:22:22.233
he'd like me
to assume bird form,

01:22:22.320 --> 01:22:23.753
preferably caged.

01:22:23.920 --> 01:22:25.990
He'd like you to make your
way into a lockable room,

01:22:26.080 --> 01:22:27.513
such as the parlor...

01:22:27.680 --> 01:22:29.318
as he won't release Jake
if he fears

01:22:29.400 --> 01:22:30.880
an attack could be mounted
upon him...

01:22:30.960 --> 01:22:32.632
once he loses his leverage.

01:22:33.320 --> 01:22:34.594
Correct, Mr. Barron?

01:22:35.960 --> 01:22:37.960
ENOCH: You're sacrificing
yourself and all of us...

01:22:38.800 --> 01:22:39.994
for Jake?

01:22:40.160 --> 01:22:42.833
Mr. Barron travels
with a Hollow, Enoch.

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:46.037
Once it arrives here,
we're all dead.

01:22:47.680 --> 01:22:50.797
Enoch. Only Jake
can see them.

01:22:50.960 --> 01:22:52.951
She means
he's our only hope.

01:23:37.320 --> 01:23:39.117
It's been my privilege...

01:23:40.040 --> 01:23:41.678
to care for you all.

01:23:44.280 --> 01:23:45.633
Goodbye, my children.

01:23:49.320 --> 01:23:50.355
(DOOR LOCKS)

01:23:55.560 --> 01:23:56.560
Now let him go.

01:24:19.880 --> 01:24:21.074
Promise me one thing, Jake.

01:24:24.720 --> 01:24:27.075
That you will try
to look after them all.

01:24:30.880 --> 01:24:32.313
I promise.

01:24:57.440 --> 01:24:58.555
(GROANS)

01:25:03.280 --> 01:25:04.599
Boo!
(CHILDREN GASP)

01:25:04.920 --> 01:25:06.797
(LAUGHING)

01:25:08.800 --> 01:25:09.800
It's getting dark.

01:25:10.200 --> 01:25:12.031
You won't even be able
to see their shadows.

01:25:12.200 --> 01:25:13.269
We have to stay inside.

01:25:13.360 --> 01:25:14.952
It's the only place
we stand a chance.

01:25:15.120 --> 01:25:16.838
He's quite right.
Now, where does

01:25:16.920 --> 01:25:18.433
Miss Peregrine keep
her weapon?

01:25:18.960 --> 01:25:20.393
In there. Let's go.

01:25:20.560 --> 01:25:21.959
Now, all right, children.

01:25:22.120 --> 01:25:23.336
Make sure all the doors
are locked,

01:25:23.360 --> 01:25:25.032
and the windows are latched.

01:25:25.200 --> 01:25:27.475
Everything must be
sealed up tight. Now quickly.

01:25:27.680 --> 01:25:28.795
Quickly! Go!

01:25:28.880 --> 01:25:29.995
(GRUNTS)

01:25:39.440 --> 01:25:40.475
Here.

01:25:41.360 --> 01:25:42.918
(PHONE RINGING)

01:25:44.120 --> 01:25:46.839
Jake, I think tonight,
you better answer that.

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:48.000
Okay.

01:25:52.440 --> 01:25:53.475
Hello?

01:25:53.560 --> 01:25:54.776
(SIREN WAILING)
Hello, this is Abe.

01:25:54.800 --> 01:25:55.915
Who's that?

01:26:00.640 --> 01:26:03.552
You don't know me yet.
I'm Jake.

01:26:03.760 --> 01:26:06.911
Ah, you're new. Welcome
to the family, Jake.

01:26:07.080 --> 01:26:08.513
Now, I can't talk long...

01:26:08.720 --> 01:26:09.994
so just tell Miss Peregrine...

01:26:10.160 --> 01:26:12.151
I'm at the air base,
and I'm fine.

01:26:13.080 --> 01:26:14.149
(SIGHS)

01:26:15.040 --> 01:26:18.749
I just wanted to say
that I miss you...

01:26:19.600 --> 01:26:21.556
and if I disappointed you...

01:26:21.720 --> 01:26:23.153
I'm sorry.

01:26:24.080 --> 01:26:26.913
You're the best grandpa
in the world.

01:26:35.320 --> 01:26:36.389
(STRAINING)

01:26:40.080 --> 01:26:41.559
(GRUNTING)
Quickly.

01:26:46.320 --> 01:26:47.320
(GRUNTING)

01:26:51.440 --> 01:26:53.112
Fiona.
Got it.

01:26:54.240 --> 01:26:55.240
Miss Avocet.

01:26:56.080 --> 01:26:57.149
Now, children.

01:26:57.320 --> 01:26:59.436
Now that you're all here,
there's a few rules.

01:26:59.600 --> 01:27:01.955
Your primary job
is to stay safe.

01:27:02.120 --> 01:27:03.394
Leave the Hollow to me.

01:27:03.560 --> 01:27:05.391
I don't want to see
any heroics.

01:27:06.280 --> 01:27:08.191
Now those of you
with garden tools...

01:27:08.360 --> 01:27:10.510
I must insist that you...

01:27:11.320 --> 01:27:12.719
(GIRLS SHRIEKING)

01:27:33.440 --> 01:27:34.759
No, Enoch. Get back!

01:27:36.160 --> 01:27:37.275
ENOCH: (SHOUTS) Whoa!

01:27:37.800 --> 01:27:38.800
(SCREAMS)

01:27:39.440 --> 01:27:40.589
(ENOCH GRUNTING)

01:27:45.880 --> 01:27:46.949
(ENOCH GROANING)

01:27:54.000 --> 01:27:55.228
(HOLLOW GROWLING)

01:28:01.160 --> 01:28:02.195
Go. Get to the attic!

01:28:02.360 --> 01:28:03.395
Come on!

01:28:03.480 --> 01:28:04.515
(GRUNTS)

01:28:06.320 --> 01:28:07.320
Take her.

01:28:08.360 --> 01:28:09.759
(GROWLING)
(GRUNTING)

01:28:10.960 --> 01:28:12.632
(CHOKING)

01:28:18.920 --> 01:28:19.989
(SHRIEKS)

01:28:21.600 --> 01:28:23.397
Go. Get out!

01:28:24.600 --> 01:28:25.600
Olive, come on!

01:28:41.160 --> 01:28:42.195
Okay.

01:28:42.600 --> 01:28:43.600
All right, uh...

01:28:43.920 --> 01:28:45.592
Crap! It's almost reset!

01:28:46.200 --> 01:28:47.235
(THUNDER BREAKING)

01:28:47.400 --> 01:28:48.515
(GROWLING)

01:28:50.360 --> 01:28:52.669
Fiona, is there anything
you can do with that tree?

01:28:52.840 --> 01:28:54.512
FIONA: Yes.
JAKE: Be careful.

01:28:57.960 --> 01:28:59.234
We're going
through the windows.

01:28:59.320 --> 01:29:00.548
Let's go! Quickly!

01:29:01.000 --> 01:29:02.035
(BANGING)

01:29:04.720 --> 01:29:05.789
(GROANS)

01:29:07.320 --> 01:29:08.389
(GASPS)

01:29:08.880 --> 01:29:09.949
(EXCLAIMS)

01:29:13.320 --> 01:29:14.673
(RUSTLING)

01:29:19.200 --> 01:29:20.758
(BANGING)

01:29:21.120 --> 01:29:22.189
(HOLLOW GROWLING)

01:29:22.880 --> 01:29:24.552
(GRUNTING)

01:29:24.800 --> 01:29:25.869
Come on!

01:29:28.160 --> 01:29:29.229
(GASPS, GROANS)

01:29:36.680 --> 01:29:38.159
Claire, come on down.

01:29:43.800 --> 01:29:44.835
(GASPS)

01:29:45.000 --> 01:29:46.035
(CLATTERING)

01:29:56.160 --> 01:29:57.160
Come on!

01:29:57.680 --> 01:29:59.432
(PANTING) Be careful.

01:30:10.280 --> 01:30:11.349
(SHOUTS)

01:30:11.880 --> 01:30:13.393
Go, Fiona!

01:30:21.080 --> 01:30:22.149
Let's go!

01:30:46.160 --> 01:30:47.957
Was that...
The loop closing.

01:30:49.400 --> 01:30:50.674
It's gone.

01:31:00.720 --> 01:31:02.551
(WIND WHOOSHING)

01:31:11.920 --> 01:31:13.148
I'm sorry, Jake.

01:31:13.960 --> 01:31:15.678
What do we do now?

01:31:17.120 --> 01:31:19.270
Is there any sign of Barron
and Miss Peregrine?

01:31:19.800 --> 01:31:22.633
Gone. Barron must have
had a boat.

01:31:27.360 --> 01:31:28.839
We have to go after them.

01:31:29.440 --> 01:31:31.112
We know he's taking her
to Blackpool.

01:31:31.280 --> 01:31:33.111
MILLARD: But Blackpool
is miles away.

01:31:33.280 --> 01:31:34.576
The next ferry
doesn't go for hours.

01:31:34.600 --> 01:31:35.828
We'll never make it in time.

01:31:37.600 --> 01:31:39.556
Not unless
we go by boat, too.

01:32:11.280 --> 01:32:12.315
(GASPS)

01:32:27.960 --> 01:32:29.598
(GRUNTING)

01:32:42.600 --> 01:32:44.636
(CRANKING)

01:32:46.400 --> 01:32:47.549
(ALL SHOUTING)

01:33:17.960 --> 01:33:19.154
(BRONWYN GRUNTS)

01:33:26.200 --> 01:33:27.997
So, there's a loop
here in Blackpool.

01:33:28.200 --> 01:33:31.556
It's only six months old.
January 11th, 2016.

01:33:31.720 --> 01:33:34.518
With Miss Avocet gone,
it can't be reset.

01:33:34.680 --> 01:33:36.477
Won't the loop close?

01:33:37.160 --> 01:33:38.718
Then it's back to real time.

01:33:40.880 --> 01:33:43.030
Jake, you know what
this means, don't you?

01:33:43.720 --> 01:33:44.869
You're gonna die.

01:33:45.040 --> 01:33:46.917
That's not what I mean.

01:33:47.080 --> 01:33:48.399
We have to get
to our own time,

01:33:48.560 --> 01:33:49.560
but you don't.

01:33:50.360 --> 01:33:53.670
You can continue
to live in 2016.

01:33:53.840 --> 01:33:55.432
But why would I do that?

01:33:55.600 --> 01:33:57.192
If we kill Barron...

01:33:57.400 --> 01:34:00.039
he'll be gone,
but time will carry on.

01:34:00.760 --> 01:34:02.557
He won't go to Florida...

01:34:03.400 --> 01:34:07.188
Abe won't die,
and you can go home.

01:34:08.880 --> 01:34:11.075
I could see my grandpa.

01:34:15.720 --> 01:34:18.234
Listen, I can explain
everything to them.

01:34:18.400 --> 01:34:21.358
I can persuade them to take
me to the island and...

01:34:21.520 --> 01:34:23.556
Wait, will you
still be there?

01:34:25.200 --> 01:34:27.395
Our old loop's gone for good.

01:34:28.400 --> 01:34:30.356
We wouldn't see
each other again.

01:34:32.080 --> 01:34:34.230
I thought you wanted me
to stay.

01:34:36.960 --> 01:34:39.190
I know you'll choose Abe.

01:34:39.920 --> 01:34:42.753
If I minded,
I wouldn't have told you.

01:34:51.560 --> 01:34:53.232
So, have you found
Miss Avocet's

01:34:53.320 --> 01:34:54.594
loop on the map yet?

01:34:55.480 --> 01:34:57.311
It's here. But it's new.

01:34:57.480 --> 01:34:59.948
She made it early this year.
That's my year.

01:35:00.120 --> 01:35:01.560
If we don't get out
before it closes,

01:35:01.640 --> 01:35:03.392
we're stuck
in January 2016.

01:35:03.480 --> 01:35:04.515
Great.

01:35:04.600 --> 01:35:06.352
Time catches up
with all of us,

01:35:06.440 --> 01:35:08.271
we all die,
except you. Plan?

01:35:08.760 --> 01:35:10.478
The loop closes at 4:30.

01:35:10.680 --> 01:35:11.874
That means
we need to get in,

01:35:11.960 --> 01:35:13.400
rescue the Ymbrynes
and then get out.

01:35:14.120 --> 01:35:16.076
Yeah, if we're not
already dead.

01:35:16.240 --> 01:35:18.000
Miss Avocet said the machine
is in the cellar

01:35:18.120 --> 01:35:19.296
of the Blackpool Tower
building.

01:35:19.320 --> 01:35:22.073
That means we will be
indoors... with Hollows.

01:35:22.240 --> 01:35:24.595
JAKE: No, we won't.
I've got a plan.

01:35:24.760 --> 01:35:26.273
But I'm gonna need your help.

01:35:56.880 --> 01:35:58.518
JAKE: This can't be it,
can it?

01:35:59.120 --> 01:36:01.076
Loop entrances
can be anywhere.

01:36:01.160 --> 01:36:03.355
The one in London's
in a subway tunnel.

01:36:16.040 --> 01:36:17.359
Are you sure this is it?

01:36:18.680 --> 01:36:19.829
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

01:36:20.400 --> 01:36:22.197
EMMA: I think so.

01:36:24.040 --> 01:36:26.395
Millard, there's something
I need you to do first.

01:36:26.560 --> 01:36:28.869
MILLARD:
(SIGHS) All right. I know.

01:36:32.240 --> 01:36:34.754
JAKE: Look. There's the tower.
It's not far.

01:36:34.920 --> 01:36:37.593
MILLARD: Easy for you to say.
I'm freezing.

01:36:43.720 --> 01:36:44.869
Ready?

01:36:55.880 --> 01:36:58.189
All of the doors
to the cellar are locked.

01:36:58.360 --> 01:37:00.400
The only way to reach the
Ymbrynes is through there.

01:37:01.040 --> 01:37:02.359
It's backstage.

01:37:02.520 --> 01:37:04.556
MILLARD: How many Hollows
can you see?

01:37:05.520 --> 01:37:07.351
JAKE: Four. That's good news.

01:37:07.920 --> 01:37:09.148
EMMA: I think you and I have

01:37:09.240 --> 01:37:10.912
a very different definition
of good news.

01:37:11.080 --> 01:37:14.231
It means Barron's other
friends haven't arrived yet.

01:37:14.400 --> 01:37:16.072
So they haven't started
the experiment.

01:37:16.960 --> 01:37:18.393
We're not too late.

01:37:20.240 --> 01:37:21.240
Okay, Emma.

01:37:21.920 --> 01:37:23.638
You ready?
You know what to say.

01:37:23.800 --> 01:37:25.119
MILLARD: Here, Jake.

01:37:27.560 --> 01:37:31.030
Our brethren should be
joining us momentarily.

01:37:31.240 --> 01:37:32.798
This is a day to...
EMMA: Hey!

01:37:32.960 --> 01:37:34.473
You down there!

01:37:34.600 --> 01:37:37.068
We killed your Hollow friend,
Mr. Barron.

01:37:37.240 --> 01:37:39.754
And now we've come
for Miss Peregrine.

01:37:39.920 --> 01:37:41.433
Bring her
and all the other Ymbrynes

01:37:41.560 --> 01:37:43.596
to the end of the pier
in five minutes...

01:37:43.760 --> 01:37:45.478
or face the consequences.

01:37:49.640 --> 01:37:51.198
These children must be

01:37:51.280 --> 01:37:53.316
as insane as their
headmistress. (CHUCKLES)

01:37:53.920 --> 01:37:57.799
Still, the Hollows
will be glad of a feed.

01:38:00.640 --> 01:38:02.278
Where are you?

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:05.798
I know you're in here
somewhere!

01:38:07.640 --> 01:38:08.709
BARRON: A-ha!

01:38:08.800 --> 01:38:10.916
Good. Listen to me.

01:38:11.080 --> 01:38:14.959
I want you to follow
Mr. Archer and Mr. Clark.

01:38:15.120 --> 01:38:16.880
They're going to take you
down to the pier...

01:38:17.000 --> 01:38:20.151
for a little afternoon tea.

01:38:21.040 --> 01:38:22.996
Mr. Archer, Mr. Clark...

01:38:23.160 --> 01:38:25.196
gather the Hollows
and take them to the pier.

01:38:25.360 --> 01:38:27.749
Those children
killed Malthus?

01:38:27.960 --> 01:38:29.313
Barron's had it in
for Malthus

01:38:29.440 --> 01:38:31.158
ever since he killed
Abe Portman.

01:38:31.320 --> 01:38:33.311
I tracked Abe Portman
for months.

01:38:35.440 --> 01:38:36.998
All I needed
was a few minutes...

01:38:37.160 --> 01:38:40.038
to get the location of Miss
Peregrine's loop from him.

01:38:40.200 --> 01:38:41.474
But no!

01:38:41.680 --> 01:38:43.511
Malthus couldn't wait.

01:38:44.000 --> 01:38:45.149
Instead...

01:38:46.120 --> 01:38:49.556
I had to masquerade
as a psychiatrist...

01:38:49.720 --> 01:38:52.109
for three weeks...

01:38:52.320 --> 01:38:53.673
in Florida!

01:38:55.640 --> 01:38:57.517
Have you ever
been to Florida?

01:39:01.560 --> 01:39:04.393
Did I not tell you to
gather the Hollows?

01:39:04.560 --> 01:39:05.560
What if it's a trap?

01:39:05.720 --> 01:39:07.836
Of course, it is, Miss Edwards.
But what of it?

01:39:08.040 --> 01:39:10.395
A couple of children
against four Hollows.

01:39:10.560 --> 01:39:12.073
Let's get this over with.

01:39:14.520 --> 01:39:16.192
(BULBS SHATTERING)

01:39:17.520 --> 01:39:18.919
(PANTING)

01:39:25.200 --> 01:39:26.519
(CROWD MURMURING)

01:39:29.880 --> 01:39:30.880
(EMMA GRUNTS)

01:39:31.720 --> 01:39:32.720
Jake, I'm stuck!

01:39:39.240 --> 01:39:40.240
Hurry up!

01:39:41.520 --> 01:39:42.748
(BELL RINGING)
Come on.

01:39:44.200 --> 01:39:45.838
(BELL RINGING)
MAN: Watch out!

01:39:59.400 --> 01:40:00.400
(CROWD GASPS)

01:40:01.760 --> 01:40:02.829
They're coming!

01:40:02.920 --> 01:40:04.273
(BOTH GRUNT)

01:40:17.920 --> 01:40:18.920
Let's go.

01:40:19.080 --> 01:40:20.080
(CLAMORING)

01:40:27.120 --> 01:40:28.872
Enoch. Now!

01:40:47.640 --> 01:40:48.640
Go! Now!

01:41:01.800 --> 01:41:02.949
Starting to see them now.

01:41:05.960 --> 01:41:06.960
Phase two.

01:41:12.120 --> 01:41:13.120
Emma, go.

01:41:16.840 --> 01:41:18.796
Don't just stand there.
Get them!

01:41:32.000 --> 01:41:33.558
(CROWD SCREAMING)

01:41:39.040 --> 01:41:40.712
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

01:41:45.840 --> 01:41:46.840
(GROWLING)

01:41:53.720 --> 01:41:55.233
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

01:41:59.000 --> 01:42:00.399
(GROANING)

01:42:11.000 --> 01:42:12.672
(SCREAMING)

01:42:36.240 --> 01:42:37.240
(GROWLING)

01:42:51.760 --> 01:42:52.909
(GRUNTS)

01:43:05.600 --> 01:43:08.558
All right. Good job, guys.
It's time for step two.

01:43:08.720 --> 01:43:10.119
Save Miss Peregrine!

01:43:10.280 --> 01:43:11.793
That's sort of step three.

01:43:11.920 --> 01:43:13.592
First, we've got to deal
with Barron.

01:43:14.480 --> 01:43:15.799
Come on.

01:43:17.960 --> 01:43:19.757
They should've been
back by now.

01:43:19.960 --> 01:43:21.313
I said it was a trap.

01:43:21.480 --> 01:43:22.959
If that's true...

01:43:23.920 --> 01:43:26.798
perhaps we should
move the Ymbrynes now.

01:43:26.960 --> 01:43:28.313
MISS EDWARDS:
You're not serious?

01:43:28.480 --> 01:43:30.789
Do I not look serious?

01:43:30.960 --> 01:43:34.316
Do I not look like a man
who has searched the globe...

01:43:34.520 --> 01:43:36.988
looking for just
one more eye to eat...

01:43:37.640 --> 01:43:39.949
in hopes of regaining
sufficient humanity...

01:43:40.120 --> 01:43:42.236
to return to his research?

01:43:42.440 --> 01:43:45.000
A man who's spent years
hunting Ymbrynes...

01:43:45.160 --> 01:43:47.993
in preparation
for this night...

01:43:48.200 --> 01:43:50.953
and two, no, three days,
in Wales...

01:43:51.160 --> 01:43:53.674
pretending to look at birds!

01:43:53.840 --> 01:43:55.193
I assure you...

01:43:55.360 --> 01:43:57.590
I will not stand idly by...

01:43:58.640 --> 01:44:02.155
to see my destiny derailed.

01:44:03.960 --> 01:44:05.996
(SCREAMING)

01:44:08.960 --> 01:44:10.154
Hugh, do it now!

01:44:13.160 --> 01:44:14.991
(BOTH GRUNTING)

01:44:21.000 --> 01:44:22.000
(SCREAMING)

01:44:24.680 --> 01:44:25.829
Come back here!

01:44:26.000 --> 01:44:27.000
Get them!

01:44:34.840 --> 01:44:35.840
Go. Get down!

01:44:38.320 --> 01:44:41.676
BARRON: You think you can
stand in my way?

01:44:42.160 --> 01:44:46.039
You, Jake,
content to age and die...

01:44:46.200 --> 01:44:49.954
as if you had not the gift
of peculiarity at all?

01:44:50.040 --> 01:44:51.040
(GRUNTS)

01:44:53.040 --> 01:44:54.234
(LAUGHS)

01:44:55.240 --> 01:44:58.550
I am a higher being.

01:44:58.720 --> 01:45:01.871
I hold the secret
to eternal life!

01:45:02.040 --> 01:45:03.189
Sorry to interrupt.

01:45:03.720 --> 01:45:05.199
What the...

01:45:05.360 --> 01:45:06.713
(EXCLAIMING)

01:45:09.720 --> 01:45:10.869
(BOTH GRUNTING)

01:45:16.520 --> 01:45:17.520
JAKE: Bronwyn.

01:45:22.680 --> 01:45:23.680
Huh!

01:45:23.760 --> 01:45:25.239
You missed me again, Jake.

01:45:25.400 --> 01:45:28.551
I take it accuracy
is not your peculiarity.

01:45:28.680 --> 01:45:30.079
(GROANS)

01:45:30.800 --> 01:45:32.074
(SNARLS)

01:45:36.280 --> 01:45:37.429
(BOTH GRUNT)

01:45:39.040 --> 01:45:42.350
(CHUCKLES) Abe was
a much worthier adversary.

01:45:45.760 --> 01:45:47.751
Don't let him
get to the birds.

01:45:48.440 --> 01:45:50.317
(GROANING)

01:45:51.280 --> 01:45:52.918
(LAUGHING)

01:45:57.240 --> 01:45:58.958
Ooh. Hmm.

01:45:59.560 --> 01:46:02.233
You must put me
in contact with your tailor.

01:46:04.280 --> 01:46:07.955
Ymbrynes, Ymbrynes!
Here I come!

01:46:13.800 --> 01:46:15.153
(SCREAMS)

01:46:20.320 --> 01:46:21.389
Cold?

01:46:21.600 --> 01:46:23.955
Wait till the blood
freezes in your veins.

01:46:24.120 --> 01:46:25.235
Hey!

01:46:28.640 --> 01:46:30.680
